<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sao Tome Puzzled Over Belgian Mandate of Capture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Sao Tome and Principe said
Wednesday that it was puzzled by the order for worldwide arrest
issued by the Belgian government to capture the former governor of
the Sao Tome Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan News Agency ANGOP reported that Sao Tome confirmed
Belgium's move but its Chief Justice Paulo Jorge noted that the
case of the financial scandal with the involvement of former
governor Carlos Queresma should be tried in his own country.
</P>
<P>
The chief justice said the case is under investigation and the
governor was dismissed in this March for his involvement in the
alleged financial scandal.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the reports which says "Queresma is now at large",
adding that the governor is now detained.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the Belgian government may take some
measures to prevent the suspect from fleeing if it agrees to
cooperate with the Sao Tome authorities.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the Belgian police arrested three foreign
 nationals hot handed in illegal financial trading, recovering
five-million- U.S. dollar treasury bills issued by Sao Tome and
Principe.
</P>
<P>
Queresma said that he had issued the bills to the three foreign
 nationals (one American, one French and the other Belgian) only
to collect the much-needed foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that President Miguel Trovoada and two prime
ministers, Armindo Vaz Dalmeida and Raul Braganca Neto knew about
the matter. But all of them denied.
</P>
<P>
The tiny Atlantic island country has only a total of 15 million
dollars in its foreign exchange reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
