<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Trys to Tackle Barriers to European Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body said here Wednesday that it has approved a
framework for the next phase of its market access strategy in a
bid to secure better access to world markets for European
exporters.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission said that it is now focusing its
efforts on a targeted program of barriers removal. "This will mean
concentrating on a limited number of economically important
priority cases where the European Union can expect to achieve
concrete results in the near future," it said.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of a set of key economic and legal criteria, the
EU branch said it will now draw up a target list of key barriers
to be tackled through the World Trade Organization (WTO), bilateral
action and the development of market access packages with non-WTO
countries.
</P>
<P>
EU trade commissioner Sir Leon Brittan said in a statement that
the EU had made a highly encouraging start with the market access
strategy but the bloc "can and must do more".
</P>
<P>
"It is now time to move to the next phase. I believe that by
concentrating our efforts, we can make a major step towards
tackling the more important specific barriers to our export
markets. This will also make an important positive contribution to
further market-opening negotiations in the forthcoming Millennium
Round of trade talks in the WTO," Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Millennium Round of WTO's multilateral trade
talks will start at the ministerial level to be held in Seattle,
the United States, in November this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, the EU has so far been able to
solve or make significant progress on nearly 250 individual trade
cases, using the full range of bilateral and multilateral
instruments at its disposal. Since 1996, the EU's executive body
has launched 41 dispute settlement consultations while requesting
11 panels in the WTO, and has participated in a further 39
consultations and panels launch by other WTO members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
