<HEADLINE> Albright Consults Allies, Aides on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Wednesday spoke to the Greek and Canadian
foreign ministers on the Kosovo crisis in advance of their trips
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that the United
States remains pessimistic that Belgrade is about to agree to NATO
conditions for an end to its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told a briefing that the U.S. does not believe "there has
been sufficient movement in the position of Belgrade on the key
points to justify any overwhelming optimism or any optimism at
all."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Albright also spoke to Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott, who had talks in Moscow earlier in the week
and is now in Germany for Kosovo consultations.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou and Canadian Foreign
Minister Lloyd Axworthy are expected to visit Moscow, hoping that
Russia might persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
accept NATO's conditions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Albright also spoke to Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott, who had talks in Moscow earlier in the week
and is now in Germany for Kosovo consultations.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Talbott and the Russians discussed details of how to
implement an agreement once Belgrade accepts NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
NATO has demanded the Serbian withdrawal from Kosovo and
agreement to let ethnic Albanian refugees go home. 
</P>
