<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Other Side of Africa's Negative Image is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- American conceptions of Africa are
frequently formed through the prism of television news cameras,
which by nature are mostly drawn to human tragedy, including armed
conflicts and civil strife.
</P>
<P>
But while the camera doesn't lie, its lens captures a
relatively narrow field, often missing a quite different dimension
of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The five-day "Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," which
concluded here on Wednesday, is aimed at an improved image that
Americans have of Africa as well as more trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
A broader view reveals a continent where some countries, such
as Botswana, Gabon, Ghana, Mauritius and Namibia, are success
stories in promoting economic growth and political stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Africa is a continent with vast natural and human resources. If
Africa's 700 million people share anything, it's a strong desire
to leverage that natural abundance into infrastructure and
enterprises that generate wealth and sustained prosperity.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill its economic promises, however, emerging Africa
clearly requires much greater investment, in particular by the
U.S. businesses. Equally important that is a U.S. government that
backs its words with deeds, and truly committed to what President
Bill Clinton recently called "a new era of partnership."
</P>
<P>
The five-day gathering follows on the heals of the U.S.-Africa
Ministerial Meetings held in Washington last month. Both events
are seen here as an integral part of the effort by the Clinton
administration to redefine the U.S.-African relationship.
</P>
<P>
Rodney Slater, secretary of transportation, William Richardson,
secretary of energy, and William Daley, secretary of commerce, and
several cabinet members of the U.S. Government, who were present
at the meeting, all acknowledged that the growth of U.S. trade and
investment in Africa is also beneficial to the United States, such
creating much more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In attendance too were executives from some of America's
largest corporations. Some two dozens of practical workshops were
held to deal with the complexities of African-American trade.
</P>
<P>
Most important is the private time between leaders from the two
sides of the Atlantic. Frank and open dialogue is the best way to
start cutting through the tangle of regulations currently limiting
trade and boosting the confidence of potential investors.
</P>
<P>
There are concrete reasons for renewed confidence. While
economic growth in many African nations was measured inactive
numbers only a decade ago -- and in general remain much too low --
several countries now sport growth rates in excess of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, not all Americans have been aware the fact that
assisting Africa would be a beneficial piece of U.S. foreign
policy. For instance, the U.S. Congress is considering a measure
called the African Growth and Opportunity Act. It eliminates many
barriers to free trade with Africa and contains features that will
simulate African economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has spoken in favor of the bill, but
the Congress is not likely to pass it very soon. Its passage
apparently faces one peculiar problem. Since the United States
hasn't passed significant trade legislation in five years, there's
a pent-up inclination to attach other trade measures to the
African bill. Some of these issues will generate heavy opposition,
the attachments threaten to drag down a worthwhile piece of
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The Congress should pass the Growth and Opportunity Act, taken
the quick trade victory and deal with other issues later. This
would send a strong signal to Africa, indicating that America now
realizes there is more to the continent than what they see through
the lens of a television news camera.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
