<HEADLINE> Solana Says NATO, EU to Work for Security Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The NATO Secretary-General,
Javier Solana, said here Wednesday that the western alliance had
set out a perspective as to how NATO and the European Union (EU)
can work together to build the European Security and Defence
Identity of the future in a Trans-Atlantic context and in a way
which will involve all allies.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief told reporters that the alliance in Washington
set its vision of "a South-East Europe that would be at peace,
stable, prosperous and increasingly integrated into the European
mainstream".
</P>
<P>
"We will work hand in hand with the other institutions to
achieve this vision. But NATO will have an important role to
play," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO welcomed the proposal of the European Union to
convene a conference on a stability pact for South-Eastern Europe
on May 27. "EU foreign ministers have also agree to consider ways
of strengthening their relations with Albania and the former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Chief also said the new strategic concept the allies
proposed during the Washington summit last week would give NATO
the ability to shape the international security agenda.
</P>
<P>
During his first briefing at NATO headquarters after the
Washington summit, Solana also said the NATO needs to look ahead
to the process of reconstruction of Yugoslavia "that must follow
the end of Kosovo crisis".
</P>
<P>
"The G7 and financial institutions like the World Bank and the
IMF stand ready to offer their financial help and practical advice
to the countries of the region," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
