<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Security Council Permanent Members Must Forge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 28 (Xinhua)--A political resolution to the Kosovo
crisis will be possible only if the five permanent members of the
United Nations are in a unity, U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
said Wednesday in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing after his meeting with German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, Annan said: "It is only when the
Council comes together and the whole world cooperates on this
issue that we are likely to make progress."
</P>
<P>
Among the five permanent members in the Security Council,
Russia and China are strongly against the NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia, while United States, Britain and France have launched
the air campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Schroeder agreed that the long and complex process to
solve the crisis just began, and there would be no swift success.
</P>
<P>
" We are at the early stage yet and I'd not want anyone to have
unrealistic expectations of immediate success," Annan said, adding
that the mediation would be "long, complex, and drawn out".
</P>
<P>
Annan praised Russia's role in seeking to resolve the crisis
with saying it was "constructive and useful". He is due to visit
Russia later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian mediator Viktor Chernomyrdin will arrive in Bonn on
Thursday for talks on Kosovo crisis, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
There were three candidates for the post of United Nations
Kosovo envoy, though it remained unclear whether all of them were
available, Annan told the press.
</P>
<P>
The three are former Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky,
former Swedish Prime Minister karl Bildt and acting Swiss Foreign
Minister Flavio Cotti.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he would soon recommend one of them to the U.N.
Security Council, and he was considering the Slovak Foreign
Minister Eduard Kukan as deputy envoy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
