<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Supports Saudi Bids for WTO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 28 (Xinhua) -- France Wednesday promised
to support Saudi Arabia in its bid to join the World Trade
Organization (WTO), according to Saudi Press Agency monitored
here.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made by visiting French Secretary of State
for Foreign Affairs Jacques Bondoux in his meeting with Saudi
Crown Prince and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and the WTO have conducted, during the past
four years, five rounds of negotiations on Riyadh's accession
to the organization. The WTO has been requiring Saudi Arabia
to be flexible in its trade policies to ensure conformation
with the terms of membership.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Bondoux also conveyed Prince Abdullah a
message from French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who expressed
Paris' position on ways of cementing bilateral ties,
international developments of common concern and the on-going
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The French official also held separate talks early in the
day with Saudi Minister of Trade Osamah Faqih on means of
promoting economic, trade and investment cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Faqih urged France to increase investment in the Gulf
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
France is one of Saudi Arabia's largest trade partners.
Bilateral trade between the two countries amounted to 3.76
billion dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
