<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Constitutional Reform Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
gazetted the terms of reference of the commission appointed to
deal with constitutional reform under the Commissions of Inquiry
Act, Minister Without Portfolio Eddison Zvobgo said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana that the
chairman of the commission is Justice Godfrey Chidyausiku, who
will be helped by three vice-chairpersons.
</P>
<P>
Other members of the commission include legislators, and
representatives of political, social and economic groups.
</P>
<P>
The commission will review the constitution and investigate
functions and powers of the executive, the legislature and the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Plenary sessions will be convened by the commission to
establish modes of operation and create panels for the purpose of
gathering evidence to produce a people-oriented constitution, said
the minister.
</P>
<P>
The commission will compile a report of findings from
individual people and public gatherings and make specific
recommendations which shall take the form of a complete draft
constitution for Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The report will be submitted to President Robert Mugabe not
later than November 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution will replace the one inherited from the
Lancaster House conference which led to the independence of
Zimbabwe in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
