<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Honored for Primary Education Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has been honored for its
achievements in primary education since the introduction of the
Universal Primary Education (UPE) two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Education Now Pencil award, first of its kind, has been
bestowed on Uganda by the World Bank and Oxfam, a British
non-governmental organization, in Washington, the United States, a
press release from the President's Office said Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The two agencies paid tribute to Uganda for having raised
primary school enrolment from 54 percent to more than 90 percent
of all primary school- going age within just two years.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has now become a case study of an effective national
commitment to education, Oxfam President Raymond Offenheiser was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
By setting up the Poverty Action Fund, Uganda has used the
additional resources made available through debt relief to invest
in its own people and pay for the fund, thus demonstrating that a
nation can use debt relief to improve its education system.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the award on behalf of Uganda, Ugandan First Lady
Janet Museveni referred to universal primary education as the most
important legacy any government in the developing world can leave
in place.
</P>
<P>
Education is a powerful weapon of liberation because it gives
people a voice and enables them to improve their lives, she added.
</P>
<P>
The Education Now Pencil is part of Oxfam's campaign to support
efforts to see that every school-aged child in the world goes to
primary school.
</P>
<P>
The campaign promotes the idea of using debt relief to mobilize
 resources to expand education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
