<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Import Maize to Ease Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The government of Tanzania
has entered into contracts with four companies to import 100,000
tons of maize at a cost of 15.6 million U.S. dollars to alleviate
the shortage of food in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Cooperatives, Ismail
Ivwata, told reporters in here Wednesday that the move came after
an appeal made by the Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye to import
200,000 tons of emergency food.
</P>
<P>
More than one million people across the country have been
plagued by a crop failure due to a drought starting last October,
while the government's own grain reserves have been virtually
depleted.
</P>
<P>
Under the contracts, each of the companies would import 25,000
tons of maize, with each ton valued at between 135 U.S. dollars
and 176.5 U.S. dollars, Ivwata said.
</P>
<P>
He named the contracted companies as EECO Traders of Britain,
Andrea &AMP; CIE SA, Mbutano Investment Company, and Sky Coach
Services Limited.
</P>
<P>
The deputy agriculture minister said that food situation in
several regions especially Dodoma and Tabora and some districts in
Morogoro, Mbeya, Arusha, Iringa, Coast and Kilimanjaro regions is
still a problem of concern.
</P>
<P>
According to assessment made by the ministry, the Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the World Food Program (WFP),
Tanzania is short of 600,000 tons of food in the first half of
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
