<HEADLINE> PM: Greece Not to Join NATO Operations Against Yugoslavia. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis reiterated here Wednesday that Greece would not
participate in any NATO military operations against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ruling Panhellenci Socialist Movement's
parliamentary group, Simitis warned that the dramatic development
in Yugoslavia had influence on the entire Balkan region and
constituted a potential threat to both the Balkans and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Greece's policy towards the crisis in Yugoslavia was based on
the need of a political solution the humanitarian problems, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Greece is pursuing these objectives with
intense diplomatic activities at all levels in cooperation with
other European countries.
</P>
<P>
As for the refugee problem resulting from NATO's airstrikes on
Yugoslavia, the prime Minister said that only all the relevant
countries make joint efforts could the refugees stay as near as
possible from their homes, and return home eventually.
</P>
<P>
On NATO's weekend summit in Washington, Simitis said NATO's new
role of "crisis handling" raised the question of the legal basis
for any intervention.
</P>
<P>
He added that everyone agreed the legal basis must be the rules
of international law and the U.N. Charter. 
</P>
