<HEADLINE> Landing Gear Suspected in F-16 Crash in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A landing gear problem is
being blamed for the latest crash of an F-16 jet fighter at Luke
Air Force Base in Arizona State of the United States, U.S. Air
Force officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-million-U.S.-dollar fighter crashed Monday while on a
training mission, the sixth such crash in six months. Both pilots
of the jet fighter ejected safely.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force grounded about 200 F-16s and ordered
inspections for about 100 equipped with similar landing gear.
</P>
<P>
It's the second grounding and mass inspection this month. After
a crash on March 26, inspectors found hairline cracks in the
engines of 18 of the 190 F-16s at Luke equipped with Pratt &AMP;
Whitney 220 engines.
</P>
<P>
The plane involved in the latest crash had passed the engine
inspection. Four of five crashes have been linked to engine
trouble.
</P>
<P>
Luke is the premier training ground for F-16 pilots in the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
