<HEADLINE> UNESCO Criticizes NATO Bombing of Yugoslav TV Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Director General of the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural organization
(UNESCO), Federico Mayor, Wednesday criticized the NATO bombing of
one of Yugoslavia's official television stations.
</P>
<P>
``Once more, we have seen that the media, official or
independent, are paying a heavy price to the war,'' said Mayor in
a communique.
</P>
<P>
``The freedom of expression and the pluralism of the media are
the fundamental objectives of UNESCO, whose constitutional act
guarantees the free circulation of ideas, by word and by image,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that whatever the political situation it is in a state,
nothing could justify the attacks or destructions of the buildings
housing the media.
</P>
<P>
``The media should not be considered as military targets...
Journalists who accomplish dangerous professional missions in the
zones of armed conflict are considered as civilians protected by
the Geneva Convention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO destroyed a great part of the building housing the
official Serb television station in Belgrade last week, killing at
least 10 people working in the building. 
</P>
