<HEADLINE> China: Developed Nations Should Take Lead in Reducing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The developed countries
should take lead in adopting measures to reduce and change their
unsustainable patterns of consumption and production, China
stressed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 7th Session of the United Nations Commission on
Sustainable Development (UNCSD), Chinese delegate Zhong Shukong
said the developed countries failed to fulfill their commitments
demanded by the UNCSD of 1992 by enhancing their levels of
unsustainable patterns of consumption and production.
</P>
<P>
Zhong said the excessive growth of car consumption and
production was a case in point.
</P>
<P>
In the interests of the future of humankind and of protecting
the earth, the current session of UNCSD should urge the developed
countries to take effective measures, in line with Agenda 21
adopted by UNCSD in 1992, to reduce and change their unsustainable
patterns of consumption and production without any further delay,
Zhong added. 
