<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Decision on Statehood Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official said a
statement on Palestinian statehood can be finalized at the
Wednesday evening meeting of the Palestinian Central Council
(PCC).
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Palestinian National Authority Ahmed
Abdurrahman told Xinhua that a committee was formed to phrase out
a final statement that is still under general debate.
</P>
<P>
The 124-member Palestinian Central Council is an intermediary
body between the ruling Palestine Liberation Organization
Executive Committee and Palestinian National Council.
</P>
<P>
The PCC, which is to make a final decision on whether to
declare an independent state on May 4 when the five-year interim
self-rule period under the 1993 Oslo Accord expires, wound up its
third session of debate Wednesday afternoon without any decision.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat repeatedly hinted declaration
of a state on May 4 and traversed the globe to rally support for
the move.
</P>
<P>
But some countries suggested that the Palestinian side postpone
statehood proclamation to avoid complicating the already fragile
situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to
take tough actions against the possible Palestinian step,
including annexing parts of the West Bank that are still under
Israel's control.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Palestinian Democratic Front Kassi Abdul-Karim
said a decision should be unanimously adopted due to its
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that there are three options in this respect.
</P>
<P>
First, the session of the council can last till early June so
that a final decision can be taken in the light of the results of
the coming Israeli general elections on May 17.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the PCC starts to work out the phraseology of
the Palestinian constitution and laws.
</P>
<P>
Second, the PCC can set a deadline for the declaration of an
independent state according to the developments of the situation
or mandate the PLO Executive Committee to do so.
</P>
<P>
Third, the PCC sticks to May 4, the date previously slated for
statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
All the participants were unanimous on the necessity of ending
the interim stage on May 4, according to Kassi.
</P>
<P>
The PCC will meet again this evening to make a final decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Arrests Suspected Israeli Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese security authorities have
arrested a woman Tuesday in southern port city of Tyre on
suspicion of being an Israeli spy, the official National News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The woman, who was questioned by State Prosecutor Adnan Addoum
Wednesday afternoon, told that her name is Mary Weizman and at the
age of 47.
</P>
<P>
She said she came to Lebanon to visit the monther of her old
friend in Beirut whom she got to know in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
She also said she entered Lebanon in a taxi from Nazareth in
northern Israel after paying 100 U.S. dollars to Israeli border
soldiers and had thrown away her Israeli passport after crossed
the border.
</P>
<P>
According to security sources, the woman, who can speak fluent
colloquial Lebanese Arabic, might be a spy of Israel's secret
service, Mossad.
</P>
<P>
She will be questioned further within the next days, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, Lebanese security forces have cracked a
number of spy rings working for Israel and arrested scores of
suspects.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Israel are officially in a state of war as the
Jewish state has been occupying part of south Lebanon for 21
years. 
</P>
