<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank to Meet U.N. on Financial Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 28 (Xinhua) --Bretton Woods leaders will
meet with the U.N. Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) to discuss
the recovery of emerging market countries hit hard by financial
contagion, and possible adjustments in global structures
monitoring finance flows and providing liquidity in emergency
situations.
</P>
<P>
ECOSOC President Paolo Fulci and U.N. Under-Secretary-General
for Social and Economic Affairs Nitin Desai announced at a press
briefing Wednesday that leaders of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and World Bank will gather here with ECOSOC officials
Thursday for the second time in a year.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus, World Bank President
James Wolfensohn, Development Committee Chairman Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda and Interim Development Committee Chairman Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi are among the panelists who will speak on behalf
of the Bretton Woods institutions.
</P>
<P>
They will travel to New York at the end of the annual meeting
of World Bank and IMF Interim and Development Committee in
Washington April 27-28.
</P>
<P>
It was said that there would be no agenda for the informal
meeting, but a document prepared by the U.N. Secretariat in 1994
suggests some likely areas of discussion.
</P>
<P>
The document covers how to promote economic recovery in
developing and transition countries, reform of international
financial architecture and increasing long-term finance flows for
development.
</P>
<P>
Debt relief for poor countries, relations between a possible
World Bank "Comprehensive Development Framework" and the U.N.'s
"Development Assistance Framework" as well as role of Bretton
Woods in the planned-for conference on "finances for development"
will probably also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The first such meeting took place in New York a year ago, which
was considered important and useful by U.N. member states and
welcomed by the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the Assembly invited the Secretary-General to
further support the Council in the organization of the high level
dialogue with the Bretton Woods institutions in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Since then consultation between the three multilateral
institutions has intensified, spurred by the unexpected length and
severity of global financials instability and its unexpectedly
harsh impact on living standards.
</P>
<P>
Preparations has already begun in the U.N. for an upcoming
world conference on the theme of "finances for development", which
would focus on issues central to the work of the World Band and
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The press will be briefed on the panel discussions at the end
of the one-day meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
