<HEADLINE> Women Play Important Role in Bangladeshi Development: Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Women are playing an increasingly
important role in the development of Bangladesh, although more
time is needed before their full potential can be realized,
speakers at a seminar said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi women contribute significantly to the development
of the country's industry, particularly in the garment and textile
industries, they told a seminar on "The Role of Women in the
Economic Development of Bangladesh and China," organized by the
Bangladesh-China Friendship Association.
</P>
<P>
Over 90 percent of the work force in the several thousand
garment and textile factories in the country are women, who have
proved their aptitude in developing skills in these fields to make
the industries competitive in the international market, they said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that women should be empowered to play their due
role in an equal manner with men, in all fields of national
planning for development, covering education, family planning,
allocation of resources and setting of development priorities and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
They admitted that the literacy rate among women in Bangladesh
is still very low, at 25.5 percent at present and more should be
done to remove illiteracy by encouraging female education.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Bangladeshi government introduced free education
and semi-scholarship for female students and since then, the
number of girl students has doubled, they said.
</P>
<P>
There are 46,000 primary schools in Bangladesh, with women
constituting 95 percent of the teachers, clearly indicating
women's role in the country's overall development, they pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seamier, Bu Jianguo, political counselor of the
Chinese Embassy in Bangladesh, said women, as an important member
of mankind, are a great force in creating human civilization and
promoting economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
She called on both the Chinese and Bangladeshi governments as
well as social organizations to promote the role of women in
social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The participants also discussed small credit and savings
schemes for women in the rural areas and women's role in family
planning in Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
