<HEADLINE> British Tourism Unaffected by London Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- British tourism authority said on
Wednesday recent racist bombings and the killing of a television
star failed to prevent overseas tourists from coming to Britain.
</P>
<P>
"We have had (telephone) calls to our New York center...but
nobody is cancelling trips as a result," said British Tourist
Authority spokeswoman Jo Leslie. "Our response is that the
bombings so far seem to be isolated to non-tourist areas."
</P>
<P>
"Our bigger concern is what is happening in the Balkans in
terms of what effect that might have on travel into Europe. It
hasn't (impacted yet), but it could well," she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, major airlines British Airways, American Airlines
and Virgin Atlantic Airways all said the high-profile violence, in
a nation which prides itself as being among the safest in the
world, had had no impact on their bookings.
</P>
<P>
"We have not noticed any impact (on bookings and arrivals) at
the moment," said Virgin Atlantic spokesman Paul Moore. "I don't
think our market is as susceptible to change as perhaps it was in
the past," he added.
</P>
<P>
British Airways said its tourist arrivals so far this month
were even one percent higher than at the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, two nail bombs exploded in London,
injuring altogether 45 people.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a leading BBC television presenter, Jill Dando, was
shot dead outside her west London home in an apparently unrelated
incident. 
</P>
