<HEADLINE> Daimler-Chrysler Profits Rise 16 Per Cent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 28 (Xinhua)--The German-U.S. automobile giant
Daimler-Chrysler reported Wednesday at its headquarters in
Stuttgart the net profits in the first quarter of year 1999 were
up 16 per cent to 2.8 billion euros (2.98 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company said in a statement the turnover in the quarter
came to 35 billion euros, up 10 per cent from the same period last
year, and the adjusted net profit was 1.6 billion euros, up 23 per
cent.
</P>
<P>
The basis for comparison were the total results of the
separated Daimler and Chrysler companies, which merged in November
1998 to form the world's third largest automobile group.
</P>
<P>
The adjusted earning per share of the company has reached 1.64
euros, up from 1.43 euros. For 1999 as a whole, Daimler-Chrysler
expects a 4-per-cent revenue rise, to 137 billion euros, and at
least the same rate of profit growth.
</P>
<P>
The company is confident that in the year 1999 it will surpass
this target, Daimler-Chrysler chairman Juergen Schremp said.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairman Robert Eaton said the two sides, formerly the
German Daimler and the U.S. Chrysler, were ahead of the schedule
in completing the integration, and he was confident that the cost
advantages from the merger would be achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
