<HEADLINE> Rwandan Court Sentences 7 Genocide Suspects to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The criminal court in northern
Rwanda's Ruhengeri district Tuesday sentenced to death seven
genocide suspects accused of involvement in the genocide in the
area in April-July 1994, according to judicial sources in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The seven were part of a group of 25 genocide suspects who were
brought to court in a ''mega-trial,'' the Rwanda News Agency
Wednesday quoted the same sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
They were found guilty of five accounts including the creation
of terrorist gangs which rampaged Ruhondo commune, throwing
corpses in pit latrines, as well as illegal possession of arms.
</P>
<P>
Twelve of the 25 accused were found not guilty and subsequently
released,

while five others were sentenced to life imprisonment. One man
got a one- year jail term.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan prisons are crammed with over 124,000 genocide suspects
waiting for trial. In a two-year period, Rwandan criminal courts
have handled over 1, 000 cases, with over 150 death penalties.
Twenty-two genocide culprits were publicly executed in April of
last year.
</P>
<P>
At this pace, trials of genocide suspects could continue to the
next century, some legal experts noted.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government has an ambitious plan of accelerating
trials by resorting to traditional courts commonly known here as
''Gacaca.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
