<HEADLINE> Kuwait Bourse Plunges to Three-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Stock Exchange (KSE)
crashed to a three-year low this week, with the KSE index closing
at 1,478.5 points Wednesday, down 29.6 points or nearly 2 percent
from last week's close.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the KSE index dived to 1,477.6 points, the lowest
level within the week.
</P>
<P>
Other three indicators were also among the lowest in many
weeks. The average daily turnover this week fell to 2.08 million
Kuwaiti dinars (6.86 million U.S. dollars) from 6.12 million
dinars (20.2 million dollars) a week ago.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the volume and transactions changed hands, a drop
of nearly 50 percent was witnessed this week, during which only
61.68 million shares were traded in 1,631 deals within five days
as against 132.95 million shares in 3,217 deals in the four
trading days last week.
</P>
<P>
On the lull in KSE trading, brokers said a looming crisis
between the government and parliament had undermined the
investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members called for a grilling of Justice and
Islamic Affairs Minister, Ahmad Kulaib, over misprints of some
120,000 copies of the holy Quran.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sheikh Ali Al-Salem is also under fire for
the cancellation of a six-month-old share sale, which, opposition
parliamentarians blamed, cost some 60 million dollars of public
funds.
</P>
<P>
Stories carried by local media earlier this week said a
growing conflict between the executive and legislative authorities
might result in resignation of the cabinet and a dissolution
of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, dealers should have good reason to expect a rally for
the KSE next week, because the Kuwait bourse announced late
Wednesday a restructuring of its administration aimed at
enhancing the stock market's performance.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah had also reportedly held a successful meeting
with parliament members Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
