<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: Embargo on Northern Cyprus Backfiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said on Wednesday the longstanding economic embargo on the
Turkish Cypriots has led to the deepening of the ties between the
Turkish Cypriot side and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit made the remarks during his five-day holiday visit to
the northern third of Cyprus which is under the control of the
Turkish Cypriot side, according to Turkey's Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that as long as the embargo is there,
the ties between Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot side will improve
more and more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
He said the continuation of the embargo will help the
international community realize that the Turkish Cypriot side is a
separate state.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish State Minister Sukru Gurel, who is
accompanying Ecevit, said the embargo on the Turkish Cypriot side
has accelerated the economic integration between Turkey and the
Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have signed a series of agreements aimed at
easing the economic difficulties on the part of the Turkish
Cyriots and have decided to establish a common economic area.
</P>
<P>
The economic embargo on the Turkish Cypriot side began after
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash declared the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north after Turkey
landed its troops on and took over the northern third of the
island in 1974 in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
