<HEADLINE> U.S. Nearing Decision on Mobil-Iran Oil Swap Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- the United States is about to
make a decision on Mobil Corp's request for a "swap" oil deal with
Iran, Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are considering it and we are getting closer to a
decision," Eizenstat told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while announcing that U.S. sanctions would
be eased to permit the sale of food and medicine to Iran, Libya
and Sudan. But he said the Mobil deal was a separate case to be
considered.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, Mobil filed a request with the U.S. Treasury
Department to ship crude to northern Iran from the company's
nearby oil fields in the region and swap it for Iranian oil that
would be shipped from the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Such a move would make it easier for Mobil to get its oil out
of the Caspian Sea region, which has a lack of pipelines.
</P>
<P>
Mobil Chairman Lucio Noto has said the company's oil swaps
request could provide an opportunity for the United States to
improve its relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a great way to start some sort of limited,
controllable dialogue" with Iran, he said at the company's
shareholders meeting last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
