<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Makes Changes on Sanctions against Iran, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration on
Wednesday announced a major revision in U.S. sanctions policy that
will permit sales of food and medical items to Iran, Libya and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The new policy calls for an exemption of such items from
future sanctions, but will not affect sanctions against Iraq,
Cuba and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told reporters that
the announcement was the result of a two-year review of overall
U.S. sanctions policy which concluded that allowing food and
medicine sales to above-mentioned countries "doesn't enhance a
nation's military capability or ability to support terrorism."
</P>
<P>
In fact, banning such sales can backfire in the United States
by eroding support for its policies and resulting in lost
business for its economically hard-hit agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions change would cover sales of wheat, corn, feed,
soybeans, edible oils, meat, fish, baby food and formula. No
decision had been made on whether fertilizer, pesticides and
agricultural equipment can also be sold, Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions on the energy sectors of these countries were being
considered separately and were not affected by Wednesday's
announcement, he said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions change could clear the way for administration
approval of a request by Iran to purchase more than 500 million
U.S. dollars worth of grain and sugar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
