<HEADLINE> Armed Robberies on Rise in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Armed robberies and
residential burglaries had risen sharply in the three month period
from December 1998 to this February compared with the same period
of the previous year, police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest crime figures, armed robbery increased
from 43.8 incidents per 100,000 of the population in the three
months under review in 1997/98, to 54.3 in the same period a year
later.
</P>
<P>
House-breaking jumped from a rate of 156.5 to 169.2.
</P>
<P>
Serious assault rose from 157.6 to 161.8 and common assault
increased from 130 to 135.1.
</P>
<P>
Car hijackings rose from 7.1 to 9.1 per 100,000 and truck
hijackings rose from 2.7 to 3.5.
</P>
<P>
The Safety and Security Ministry said in a statement that 15
crime categories had stabilized for the December to February
period over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
They included murder, rape, business burglaries,
cash-in-transit robberies and drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
It said the least crime had occurred in the Northern Province
during the three-month period, while Gauteng and the Western Cape
had the highest crime rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
