<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Supports Cypriot Entry in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Italian Deputy Foreign Minister
Umberto Ranieri said here Wednesday that Italy supports Cyprus'
accession to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Ranieri made the remark after a meeting with Geroge Vassiliou,
Cypriot chief negotiator in the EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy appreciates very much the efforts made by Cyprus
to meet the accession criteria.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Cyprus can join the EU before a solution to the
Cyprus problem, Ranieri said "these are two separate issues, but
which mutually influence each other."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot south and Turkish
Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of the failed pro-Athens
coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula, but the peace talks
between the two sides have been broken up since summer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ranieri pointed out that Cyprus' political problem as a result
of the Turkish invasion has been "going on for too long," hoping
Cyprus can as rapidly as possible become a full member of the EU
and its political problem may be solved.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, Slovenia, Estonia, Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic started substantive accession negotiations with the EU in
November 1998.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Vassiliou reiterated that President Glafcos
Clerides' invitation to the Turkish Cypriots for joining forces in
the accession talks is still valid.
</P>
<P>
Ranieri arrived here ealier in the day on a two-day visit,
during which he will also inaugurate the Italian Cultural Month
on the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
