<HEADLINE> Election Day Declared Public Holiday in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's cabinet has
decided that this year's election day, June 2, will be a public
holiday.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet statement said Wednesday that the new parliament will
have its first session on June 14 to elect the new state
president, who will be sworn in on the 16th day of the month.
</P>
<P>
It was proposed that provincial legislatures would convene on
June 15 to elect their presiding officers as well as provincial
premiers.
</P>
<P>
The new president would make his inaugural address to a joint
sitting of parliament on June 25, with a debate on his address
scheduled for the following week, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is set to be the next president as
opinion polls show that his party, the African National Congress,
enjoys the support of the majority of the electorate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
