<HEADLINE> Firm Oil Stocks Pull London To 2nd Straight Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Despite London's blue chips ended
at a second straight record Wednesday, Frankfurt and Paris gave up
ground as investors took a contemplative step back.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE-100 Index crept beyond the previous session's
record closing high on the day as trading remained quiet.
</P>
<P>
Blue chip shares pushed the index to close ahead by relatively
paltry 5.2 points at 6,598.8, creating another record peak.
</P>
<P>
A rise in crude oil prices, which hit a 15-month high of 16.20
U.S. dollars a barrel Wednesday, gave a boost to oil giants BP
Amoco and Shell, whose shares rose 3.3 percent and 2.6 percent,
respectively on the London market.
</P>
<P>
The rally followed the earlier release of a survey by the
American Petroleum Institute showing a 4.2 million barrel
reduction in oil stockpiles, vs. a forecast jump of 1 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra DAX dipped after gaining almost 2 percent
Tuesday as shares in Volkswagten AG fell more than 6 percent on a
disappointing profit outlook from the carmaker.
</P>
<P>
It closed down 12.09 at 5,352.72, having moved in a range of
5,311.43-5,370.25 during the day.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, dealers saw VW's disappointing results as a reminder
of the fragility of the European economy.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 closed down 16 at 4,374.70. French automobile stocks
slid after outperforming recently in anticipation of good first
quarter sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
