<HEADLINE> House Votes to Restrict Clinton from widening Kosovo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives on Wednesday voted to limit President Bill
Clinton's ability to widen the Kosovo war, saying the president
should get congressional approval before injecting "ground
elements" into the ever-expanding conflict with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The 249 to 180 vote showed a great contrast to Clinton's
appeal for a "single voice" in Congress on the Kosovo crisis as
he said NATO had done.
</P>
<P>
Majority-party Republicans said Congress was merely exercising
its constitutional responsibility and forcing Clinton to keep
his word on not sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions set by the vote could even make it hard to use
the Apache attack helicopters that have been recently sent to
Albania, poised for attacking Serb ground forces.
</P>
<P>
"We should not even be in the Balkans," said Republican
representative Floyd Spence, chairman of the Armed Services
Committee. "The national security of this country is not at stake."
</P>
<P>
But Democrats said Clinton had promised them several hours
earlier at a White House meeting with lawmakers that he would
not attempt to put combat troops into Kosovo without first
seeking congressional consent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the White House meeting with lawmakers, Clinton
expressed reservation about measures like the one the House had
just passed, saying 19 NATO nations had expressed unity over the
weekend and "America must continue to speak with a single voice
as well."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also pressed for quick approval of his 6 billion U.S.
dollars request to pay for the expanded bombing against Yugoslavia
and urged lawmakers to resist Republican-led efforts to double it.
"We must get a Kosovo funding measure passed and to my desk now,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
