<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Finance Institutions Discuss Ways for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 50 leaders of African
micro-financial institutions, which offer under 300 U.S. dollars
loans, gathered here Wednesday to search for ways to help the
poor help themselves.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop opened Wednesday will focus on the
building of regional and country-level networks to provide more
effective and extensive loans to the poor.
</P>
<P>
"The real experts in micro-finance institutions (in Africa) are
not foreign consultants or donors. They are those struggling to
build efficient credit and savings services for the poor
majority," said Nancy Barry, president of the World Women Banking
(WWB).
</P>
<P>
Barry noted that micro-finance institutions and hundreds of
thousands of poor clients are working with governments and banks
to reshape financial sector policies and legal structures to
serve the poor in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, organized by the U.N. Development
Program (UNDP) and the World Women Banking, brought together
micro-finance leaders from 15 countries in western, southern and
eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The representatives will exchange best practice on reducing
costs while expanding micro-finance services and discuss how to
set up regional networks.
</P>
<P>
The research carried out by the World Women Banking and UNDP
indicate that more than 100 micro-finance and rural financial
institutions operate in Africa, which are reaching large number
of the poor, mostly women, with their special service.
</P>
<P>
Jennifer Riria, managing director of the Kenya Women Financial
Trust, told Xinhua that the average loan size of micro-finance
institutions is under 300 U.S. dollars, which most African banks
consider too small to lend.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the institutions don't require clients to offer a
 collateral like a house, car or other property, but only "a
guarantee from a group of 20 to 40 people", she said.
</P>
<P>
Jennifer said if the loan recipient is not able to repay the
loan and interest, the other members of the group are responsible
for the debt.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of these institutions have a repayment
rate of 90 percent or more, according to the survey by the UNDP
and the World Women Banking.
</P>
<P>
The World Women Banking, established in 1979, is a global
non-profit organization aimed at helping poor women build their
own small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
