<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Erupts in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting erupted on the
outskirts of Masiaka in Sierra Leone, a senior officer of the west
African peacekeeping force ECOMOG said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We reached the gates of the town yesterday (Tuesday) and since
then the small arms battle and artillery exchanges for the town
have intensified," a report reaching here quoted the officer as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Masiaka is on the main road from the capital Freetown to the
interior parts of the west African country and the rebels holding
the town have blocked road traffic to the interior from the
capital.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels are fighting us fiercely for the town with heavy
machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades," the officer noted.
</P>
<P>
According to military officers, ECOMOG troops and Kamajor
traditional hunters besieged the town Wednesday, shelling rebel
positions there.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fightings were also reported around the northern Sierra
Leone town of Yele in Tonkelele district following a rebel attack
Tuesday, in which at least thirty people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Septimus Kaikai, spokesman of the Sierra Leonean government,
said "the government is implementing a dual track approach,"
adding it would continue dialog with the rebels but at the same
time continue to fight to clear them from strategic positions in
the country.
</P>
<P>
In the war-ravaged country of Sierra Leone, the Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah government supported by the ECOMOG troops now holds
Freetown and its vicinity while the rebels control several
strategic points.
</P>
<P>
In a broadcast speech to mark 38 years of independence,
President Kabbah Tuesday urged the rebels to "renounce violence
and terror" and challenged them to "meet us at the polling booth
in less than 15 months' time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
