<HEADLINE> 2 Sentenced to Death in Vietnam's Smuggling Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Two defendants have been sentenced
to death at the end of the month-long trial of Vietnam's biggest
ever smuggling case, Vietnam News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ho Chi Minh City People's Court Thursday morning handed
down the capital punishment for smuggling on Tran Dam, ex-director
of the Tan Truong Sanh private company in Ho Chi Minh City which
smuggled goods worth more than 900 billion Vietnamese dong (nearly
83 million U.S. dollars) into Vietnam from 1994 to August 1997.
</P>
<P>
Phung Long That, former chief of the anti-smuggling division 1
of the Ho Chi Minh City Customs Department, also got the death
penalty for receiving bribes.
</P>
<P>
Six other defendants were sentenced to life imprisonment while
the rest received jail terms ranging from eight months to 20
years.
</P>
<P>
The number of defendants in the trial reached 74 with a series
of charges including smuggling, bribing, acting as intermediates
for bribing, hiding and selling properties acquired illegally,
abusing positions and power and hiding criminals.
</P>
<P>
Besides Tran Dam and Phung Long That, the defendants included
customs officers and officials of a number of state-owned
enterprises in Ho Chi Minh City, the central province of Thua
Thien-Hue and the southern provinces of Can Tho and Ben Tre.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 witnesses and people with related interests and
obligations testified during the trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
