<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Some 50 persons have been killed in northern and
central Afghanistan in the Taliban's jet bombardment since Tuesday,
a top opposition military commander said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Taliban jets bombed the towns of Jabel Saraj, Taluqan and
Bamiyan killing 10, 30 and 10 respectively," said General Sayed
Hussain Anwari, one of chief military commanders of the Northern
Alliance. (Afghanistan-Fighting-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi left here
Thursday evening for a week-long visit to the United States for
talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on economic issues and
global affairs.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which will take Obuchi to Los Angeles, Chicago and
Washington, is the first official visit to the United States by a
Japanese prime minister in 12 years, although Japanese prime
ministers often make working trips to the country.  (Japan-US-
Obuchi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- A NATO missile slammed into a suburb of Sofia, capital
of Bulgaria, damaging a house but causing no casualties, the
Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The AGM-88-HARM air-to-surface missile hit through the roof of
a two-story house in the western suburb of Gorna Banya at 10:00 p.
m. on Wednesday night. A child suffered shock from scare. (
Bulgaria-NATO-Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Brussels -- U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said
here Thursday that the Russians will have to make some tough
choices during their present mediation in the Kosovo Crisis.
</P>
<P>
After concluding a visit to Moscow for a peaceful solution to
the war in Yugoslavia, Talbott told reporters at the NATO
headquarters that "the Russian leadership fully understands the
importance of the role that it can play in finding a diplomatic
solution to this conflict." (Russia-Talbott-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and visiting United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan agreed Thursday that the
Yugoslavia crisis should be resolved in line with the U.N. Charter
and international law.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Annan, Yeltsin urged the world body to
play a "special" role in seeking a political solution to the
raging conflict in the Balkans, said Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov. (Russia-UN Chief) 
</P>
</TEXT>
