<HEADLINE> French Prime Minister Not Rules Out Kosovo's Breakaway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
said on Thursday that France does not exclude Kosovo's breakaway
from Yugoslavia, although it does not envisage it now.
</P>
<P>
"We don't envisage at this stage a breakaway (of Kosovo), but
we will see where we will lead this conflict," Agence France-
Presse quoted Jospin as saying during a meeting of his government
ministers on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said that France now has not changed the orientation adopted
at the Rambouillet conference two months ago, which calls for a
substantial autonomy of Kosovo under a possible provisional
administration by the international community, in particular the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for a French leader to hint at a
possible breakaway of Kosovo from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac has on several occasions
expressed his opposition to the idea of a breakaway of Kosovo from
Yugoslavia, but he has called for an EU administration in Kosovo
once a political settlement is reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
