<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Economy Expected to Grow by 6 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said on Thursday his country's economy is expected to grow by 6
percent this year and 6.8 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
"We have walked on the right path," Mubarak said in a speech to
mark the Labor Day on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians have regained confidence in the national economy,
and a new atmosphere is giving a strong push to the massive
investments in all fields, the president told 3,000
representatives of labor unions of Egypt's 22 million workers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mubarak cautioned that the Egyptian economy needs to
grow by 7-8 percent to create about 500,000 jobs a year to erase
its growing unemployment. The official unemployment rate is 10-13
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Mubarak's economic growth forecast is to be
strengthened by the domestic private sector investment, which is
seen as a sign of confidence in Mubarak's economic liberalization
program which started in 1991.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector has controlled about 71 percent of
the economy, which during his predecessors' rule was almost
entirely under state control.
</P>
<P>
The private sector investment is now 22 percent of the gross
domestic product, and the challenge is to raise it to 25 percent
so that the economy grows at about 7 to 8 percent, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's privatization program, which envisages selling off 314
inefficient state-run enterprises, has won praise from the
International Monetary Fund. The reforms also involve loosening
investment restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said a growing burden on the economy is the trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the 1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30 are
expected to reach 17.5 billion U.S. dollars while exports would
only stand at 5.14 billion dollars, Mubarak said, calling it a
"disturbing figure."
</P>
<P>
The government plans to reduce imports to 14 billion dollars
annually and increase exports to 6.3 billion dollars, he said. One
way to do it will to produce goods in Egypt that are as good as
imported ones, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
