<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militiaman Wounded in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A member of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) militia was wounded Thursday by a roadside bomb
in south Lebanon, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The SLA member was hurt when his car was hit by a roadside bomb
near Kafarhoun village just outside the Israeli occupied border
zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
claimed responsibility for the bombing, which raised the number
of wounded SLA since the start of this year to 20. A militiaman
was killed during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli forces out of the
country. 
</P>
