<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Workers Need Further Training in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong has said four out of five workers in his country need
further training and education to update their skills and they
must quickly sharpen skills and increase capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the point in his May Day Message 1999 which was
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Goh stressed that workers must continue to
learn and re-learn to keep up with the changing needs of
Singapore's economy.
</P>
<P>
"We are now strong in electronics and chemicals. For the future
we need to nurture new areas like biotechnology and the life
sciences. We will also have to focus on services like finance,
healthcare, education, logistics and IT (information technology).
These new sectors will require new skills," he said.
</P>
<P>
Goh said a knowledge economy does not mean just hi-tech
activities or jobs which require a university degree.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that a knowledge worker is one who works smartly
and learns relevant skills quickly to improve himself and to raise
his productivity.
</P>
<P>
A cleaner who knows the properties of the chemicals and the
performance of the mechanized equipment he uses to clean offices
and housing estates is a knowledge worker, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said it is more difficult to get all workers to constantly
learn new skills and acquire new knowledge than to produce a few
thousand workers with good knowledge. The prime minister stressed
that Singapore has to move the entire workforce up the knowledge
ladder, not just a few at the top, in order to continue to attract
high value investments.
</P>
<P>
"The higher our average and collective knowledge, the easier it
is for us to attract high-value investments and high-paying jobs,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
