<HEADLINE> Four Dead in Plane Crash in North England </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Four people were killed on
Thursday when a light aircraft crashed near Selby in North
Yorkshire in northern England.
</P>
<P>
The Mooney single-engined plane crashed within minutes after
taking off on its way to the Netherlands from Sherburn in Elmet,
killing all four people on baord, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Police were called by a farmer on a mobile phone who saw the
plane came down in flames between the villages of Hemingbrough and
North Duffield at Loftsome Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Divisional Commander Phil Wade of North Yorkshire
Fire Brigade, who was one of the first to reach the scene, said: "
The plane was still alight when we got there. It's possible it
could have caught fire before it came down, or when it hit the
ground - we don't know yet."
</P>
<P>
The identities of the crash victims have not been revealed,
but unconfirmed reports said they were all men, two of whom were
passengers and two crew.
</P>
<P>
Investigators said it may take days to determine the cause of
the crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
