<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Meets U.N. Chief on Yugoslavia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and visiting United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan agreed
Thursday that the Yugoslavia crisis should be resolved in line
with the U.N. Charter and international law.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Annan, Yeltsin urged the world body to
play a "special" role in seeking a political solution to the
raging conflict in the Balkans, said Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ivanov said, Annan hoped Russia will firmly
support the United Nations to play such a role. The two also
agreed that Russia and the United Nations will cooperate closely
to put an end to the Balkan crisis which has lasted more than a
month.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said both Yeltsin and Annan expressed deep concern over
the protracted Yugoslavia conflict because it has menaced global
stability and security.
</P>
<P>
They expressed confidence that a political solution to the
crisis is "in the interests of all peoples in the Balkans" and
will "help restore stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Annan that Russia will continue to provide
assistance to all victims of the conflict, which has displaced
tens of thousands of civilians in the secessionist Yugoslav
province of Kosovo, which,along with other parts of Yugoslavia,
has been bombed by NATO warplanes since March 24.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Annan earlier Thursday, Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov also urged the U.N. to play a critical
role in solving the Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told Annan that NATO should immediately halt its
destructive air campaign against Yugoslavia and that negotiations
should be held to seek agreement on Kosovo's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Wednesday night from Germany, will
travel on to London Thursday. He met Yeltsin's peace envoy Viktor
Chernormyrdin Thursday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
