<HEADLINE> 50 Killed in Taliban Jet Bombardment: Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Some 50 persons have been
killed in northern and central Afghanistan in the Taliban's jet
bombardment since Tuesday, a top opposition military commander
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Taliban jets bombed the towns of Jabel Saraj, Taluqan and
Bamiyan killing 10, 30 and 10 respectively," said General Sayed
Hussain Anwari, one of chief military commanders of the Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Anwari said the bombings Tuesday on the three towns were
ferocious and caused widespread damage to the towns' limited
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said that following the fall of Bamiyan last week, the
Taliban launched a major offensive on Darre Suf in the northern
province of Samangan in a bid to limit the advance of the Northern
Alliance toward the neighboring Balkh province.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban were dealt a heavy blow Wednesday when the
opposition troops advanced into the towns of Chapchal in Samangan
on the border with Balkh Province and Keshende in Balkh, according
to Anwari.
</P>
<P>
The general said the alliance's troops have now overrun the
town of Shebar in eastern Bamiyan, capturing Sheikh Ali in Parwan
Province near the Bamiyan border.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, Wardak Province in central Afghanistan "remains
firmly in the alliance's control," according to the general.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the Taliban's recent offensives, the alliance has lost
little territory in central and northern Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
