<HEADLINE> S. African President to Visit Pakistan Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela is to visit Pakistan early next week at the head of a
high-level delegation to discuss prospects for enhancing political
and economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Foreign Office Thursday, Mandela
will arrive here on May 4 on a day-long visit at the invitation of
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral, regional and international issues of mutual
interest, including the Kashmir dispute, will come up for
discussion during the talks between Mandela and Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, in his capacity as chairman of the Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM), called for a peaceful settlement of the Kashmir
dispute in his inaugural address to the 12th NAM Summit in Durban
in September last year.
</P>
<P>
"All of us remain concerned that the issue of Jammu and Kashmir
should be solved through peaceful negotiations and should be
willing to lend all strength we have, to the resolution of this
matter," Mandela had said, urging the 114-member grouping to lend
its full weight to "this outstanding issue which is a matter of
concern to the whole world."
</P>
<P>
Besides the political issues, the leaders of South Africa and
Pakistan will also explore possibilities of increasing commercial
and economic ties between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
