<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wages and Benefits Rise Slightly in the First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Wages and benefits for U.S.
workers rose only 0.4 percent in the first three months of the
year, indicating the lowest unemployment in 29 years is still not
generating wage pressures, the Labor Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the first-quarter gain followed a much
larger, 0.7 percent advance from the final quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the slight wage pressures is occurring at a time
of low inflation, meaning that workers' take-home-pay is not being
eroded by higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
The slack wage pressures are occurring even though the overall
unemployment rate dipped to a 29-year-low of 4.2 percent in March.
For all of last year, unemployment averaged its lowest level in
three decades.
</P>
<P>
The combination of slight wage pressure and low unemployment
has given the Federal Reserve the leeway to allow the economy to
continue growing at a rapid clip without feeling the need to start
raising interest rates to prevent inflation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Labor Department said new claims for
unemployment benefits declined by a larger-than-expected amount
last week, falling to 294,000 new claims, down 20,000 people from
the week before. It was the biggest one-week decline in three
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
