<HEADLINE> New Guidelines on Princes Issued in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Britain's press watchdog the Press
Complaints Commission issued new guidelines on Thursday about the
coverage of Princes William and Harry.
</P>
<P>
The commission urged editors to continue to show restraint on
covering news about 16-year-old William and his 14-year-old
younger brother, but called for more news to be officially
released about the princes -- sons of Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
It said reports about Prince Harry -- which included stories
about his haircut and his prowess on the soccer field -- had not
violated a tough code of practice on children of the rich and
famous adopted by the British media after the September 1997 death
of the princes' mother, Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
Both William and Harry are studying at Eton College.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Prince Charles's press office officially
dropped complaints against two newspapers -- the Mirror and the
Daily Star -- of unauthorized intrusion of Privacy of the two
princes.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted that Charles and the palace have withdrawn this
complaint, which should never have been made in the first place,"
Mirror editor Piers Morgan wrote. 
</P>
