<HEADLINE> News Analysis: PLO wisely Postpones Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA CITY, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Central Council decided here Thursday to
postpone declaration of an independent Palestinian state
proposed for May 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
The 124-member council also decided to reconvene its meeting
in June and make its final decision on the statehood issue after
Israel's elections on May 17.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council decided to form committees charged with
preparation works on statehood, such as formulating the
Palestinian constitution and election laws.
</P>
<P>
Declaring an independent Palestinian state on May 4 is a major
political issue not for the Palestinians alone, but for Israel as
well. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has stated on many
occasions that the 1993 Oslo Accords between the Palestinians and
Israel entitled him the right to do so.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has threatened to cancel the Oslo process and annex
parts of the West Bank now under its control if Arafat decides to
declare statehood on May 4, the date when the five-year
transitional period of Palestinian self-rule expires under the
Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the council's postponement decision
can not be regarded as a political defeat of the Palestinian side
facing presure and threats from Israel. Instead, it showed that
the Palestinian leadership has achieved what it has planned for.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the council's decision to keep the proceedings going
until after Israel's May general elections will keep those parties
from claiming that their strong anti-peace policy stopped the
council's declaration.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Arafat has succeeded in making a major diplomatic
and political coup on both international and domestic fronts in
the statehood issue.
</P>
<P>
His recent diplomatic efforts have left him in a strong
position to be able to declare a state with or without prior
negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the international level, he had toured countries of Arab,
Islamic, West and East, drumming up support for the Palestinian
right to declare an independent state. He specially managed to
attain a political backing from the European Union and the
United States that the Palestinian people have the right to
decide their future on their land, and the final peace talks with
Israel to be viting the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin to attend
the council meeting as observer.
</P>
<P>
Having all these jobs done, Arafat's real intention is to force
Israel to implement the signed agreements, to move the peace
process forward and force Israel to solve the remaining issues
such as the status of Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, the
settlements within a time frame through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The postponement of the decision-making until after Israeli
elections will serve all these purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
