<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flexibility for Overseas-Invested Power Plants in Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China will treat overseas-
invested power plants with "flexibility" in the on-going price
reform of electricity, a senior Chinese economic official said
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, minister in charge of the State Development
Planning Commission, told visiting Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai and the Thai delegation that China will take the concerns
of overseas-invested power plants into consideration while
carrying out the reform.
</P>
<P>
"Some overseas-invested power plants have worries as to whether
their set rate of returns will be affected by the reform," he said.
"I can say that the government will treat this problem, which left
over from the past, in a flexible manner."
</P>
<P>
Due to a power-supply shortage in the past, many overseas-
invested power plants were offered set rates of return, which
resulted in a relatively higher price for electricity, according
to the minister.
</P>
<P>
As the situation has now changed from shortage to over-supply,
problems with the price of electricity price have appeared. The
current "chaotic" pricing of electricity must be reformed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The target of the reform, Zeng said, is to separate power
plants and operators of power network. Power plants will have to
compete to win the right to enter a network, after the reform is
completed.
</P>
<P>
"A flexible treatment does not mean we encourage the set-rate
return mechanism," he said. "We hope, therefore, that overseas-
invested power plants will raise their competitiveness and take a
long-term development perspective." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pushes Ahead With Textile Industry Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China continues to slash the
production capacity of its cotton-weaving industry despite the
increasing pressures of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Du Yuzhou, director-general of the State Administration of
Textile Industry, told a press conference here today that in the
first three months of the year, China dismantled a total of 780,
000 spindles in its cotton mills and laid off 100,000 textile
workers. As a result, state-owned textile enterprises reduced
losses by 650 million yuan in the period.
</P>
<P>
Exports of textiles and garments were valued at 7.62 billion U.
S. dollars for the quarter, a decrease of 2.5 billion U.S. dollars,
or nearly one-fourth of the total, from the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Du said that retail prices of textiles continued to drop from
January to March, decreasing by 10.7 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the domestic market for textiles has grim
prospects because prices are unlikely to bounce back in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
China has targeted the textile industry as the sector for
achieving breakthroughs in turning around money-losing state-owned
enterprises. It has set the target of state-owned textile
enterprises turning losses into profits by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China exceeded the target of cutting redundant
capacity by 4.8 million spindles and streamlining textile
employment by 600,000 people. Actually, it dismantled 5.12 million
spindles, and laid off 660,000 textile workers.
</P>
<P>
However, the additional 4.4 million spindles it plans to smash
this year are mostly new and running at full capacity. A majority
of them are in mills in interior areas that are economically
lagging behind other parts of the country, and laid-off textile
workers will increase unemployment pressures in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Du said that the task of restructuring the textile industry in
the next three quarters of the year will be very arduous. The
State Administration of Textile Industry has already dispatched
work panels to various localities to supervise and push ahead the
dismantling of spindles.
</P>
<P>
He predicts that about two million more spindles will be
smashed in the first half of this year, increasing the total
number of dismantled spindles to about seven million for the 18-
month period.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the rest of the year, the textile industry
will focus on renovating product structures and exploring markets
in the rural areas, and in the fields of decorative and industrial
textiles. He also called on the industry to set up a number of
technological innovation projects to increase their
competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
