<HEADLINE> Trade Minister Urges Guangdong to Export More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Trade Minister
Shi Guangsheng on Thursday urged south China's Guangdong Province
to increase exports and attract more overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Shi made the remark during a meeting with Guangdong Provincial
Governor Lu Ruihua and many other senior local government
officials. The meeting was also attended by Vice Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Ministers Chen Xinhua and Zhou Keren.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts must be made to expand exports and lure more overseas
investment by all possible means," Shi said.
</P>
<P>
He said that policies encouraging exports and overseas funds
must be implemented by down-to-earth measures to improve the
export mix and diversify the export market.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the legal rights and interests of export
enterprises and overseas-funded firms must be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, a pioneer of China's market economy reforms, was the
country's largest exporter with a volume of more than 75 billion U.
S. dollars last year, 41.2 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Partly due to the Asian financial crisis, however, Guangdong's
exports plunged 20.5 percent in the first quarter of this year,
with the rate for exports of general goods declining by as much as
55.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, China's exports totaled 37.2 billion U.S. dollars
in the first three months this year, down 7.9 percent from a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that contracted overseas
investment in China reached 8.72 billion U.S. dollars in the first
quarter, roughly the same as in the same period last year. The
quarterly volume of actual overseas investment in China, however,
declined 14.6 percent in the first three months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
