<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Missile Hits House in Sofia's Suburbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A NATO missile slammed into a
suburb of Sofia, capital of Bulgaria, damaging a house but causing
no casualties, the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The AGM-88-HARM air-to-surface missile hit through the roof of
a two-story house in the western suburb of Gorna Banya at 10:00 p.
m. on Wednesday night. A child suffered shock from scare.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the missile was launched by a NATO plane, Bulgarian
Defense Minister Georgi Ananiev told a press conference that
Bulgaria had informed NATO of the incident, urging bilateral
coordination to prevent a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
The radar system of the Bulgarian air force spotted a NATO
plane violating the country's airspace shortly before the missile
hit Gorna Banya.
</P>
<P>
There have been several reports of NATO missiles or missile
wrecks falling into Bulgaria's territory, but Thursday's incident
was the first to have occurred near the capital, which is only 45
kilometers from the Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government has reached an agreement with NATO
allowing the alliance to use its airspace for attacks on
Yugoslavia. However, the agreement has yet to be ratified by the
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
