<HEADLINE> HK Public Confidence in Economy Improved: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Despite the difficult times,
public confidence in the economy has begun to improve in recent
weeks, Hong Kong's Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tsang told the media after chairing the Task Force on
Employment (Task Force) that contributing to the better economic
sentiments are the easing in bank liquidity and interest rates,
the stabilization of share and property prices, the tax rebate and
other measures in the budget and the results of the recent land
sales.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, whether this improvement is sustainable
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
At the Task Force on Employment, members were informed that the
number of tourist arrivals in the first three months of 1999 was
around 2.47 million, an increase of 13.4 percent as compared with
the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"A whole series of initiatives aimed at promoting Hong Kong to
visitors and enhancing Hong Kong's attractiveness has been planned
and will be actively pursued, " Tsang said. "These should
translate into more job opportunities in the industry."
</P>
<P>
As regards the capital market, small and medium enterprises
should find it easier to secure bank loans to tie over temporary
liquidity problems as a result of the improvement measures in the
Special Finance Scheme, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department's efforts to improve its employment
services have achieved encouraging results, according to Tsang. In
March, the department secured 13,000 job vacancies, an increase of
93 percent over the number secured in February. The number of
successful placements had also exceeded 3,500.  
</P>
</TEXT>
