<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Claims Growing Death Toll From Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Health Ministry report
said that death toll among children and elderly people increased
sharply in March as a result of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The report, released Thursday by the Vital and Health
Statistical Department of the Ministry, showed that some 6,400
children under the age of five died of diarrhea, pheumonia,
respiratory infections and malnutrition last March.
</P>
<P>
While in March 1989 before the U.N. sanctions were imposed on
Iraq, a total of 362 children under five died of the
above-mentioned diseases, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, more than 2,520 elderly people over
the age of 50 died of malignant neoplasms, diabetes and heart
diseases last March, compared with 513 registered deaths in March
1989.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed crippling economic sanctions on Iraq
in 1990 following its invasion of Kuwait, which touched off the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has claimed that more than 1.5 million children and the
elderly have died of various curable diseases since the
imposition of the U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
