<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renowned Chinese Writer Passes Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Renowned Chinese writer Yao
Xueyin passed away here in Beijing today at the age of 89.
</P>
<P>
Born October 10, 1910, Yao began his career as a writer in the
1930s, and had served as honorary vice chairman of the Chinese
Writers Association before death.
</P>
<P>
He published many works, and was the recipient of the "Mao Dun
Prize," the highest award for Chinese writers, for his long
historical novel "Li Zicheng."
</P>
<P>
Li Zicheng, known as "Chuang Wang" in Chinese history, was a
famous leader of the late Ming Dynasty who led an army of
rebellion made up of Chinese farmers and captured Beijing, the
Ming capital, in 1644. He died the next year after his troops were
defeated.
</P>
<P>
Yao was also well known for his achievements in Chinese history
and his studies of classic Chinese literature.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
