<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Warns Local Governments To Cease Illegal Rural Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's central government has
announced it is stepping up the nationwide crack down on local
authorities that charge farmers excessive, unfair and often
illegal fees merely to try and fill their own coffers.
</P>
<P>
It has also warned that in cases considered serious offenses,
the heads of the local authorities and the persons held directly
responsible will be dealt with harshly according to the law.
</P>
<P>
As the Ministry of Finance prepares a major shake up of its
fiscal revenue system later this year it has targeted the practice
which it says places unfair burdens on the rural communities and
has warned in an urgent circular distributed to all government
institutions today that it will no longer tolerate these
activities.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the central government's efforts to flex its
macro-economic muscles by increasing the tax base. The central
government is in the process of pushing a proposal in this respect
through the National People's Congress (NPC), China's highest
legislature.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance also announced that it is drawing up a
series of regulations that will eliminate various levels of fees
that local authorities collect from farmers but says it will
substitute some of them with a nationally levied tax.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime one of the central government's primary
economic targets this year is to raise the income of farmers. It
is aware that the country's 900 million rural residents represent
a potentially huge growth area in terms of consumer demand for
boosting the economy which is still feeling the bite of the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, per capita income of rural residents has witnessed a
decreasing growth rate in the past two years, a situation the
government wants to reverse.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance pointed out in the hard-hitting
circular that a number of local authorities have continued to
increase the burden on farmers by wantonly forcing them to pay
excessive and irrational fees, despite being repeatedly prohibited
from doing so by the central government.
</P>
<P>
These fees, which are listed under the titles of "common
production," "universal service" and "labor substitution", go far
beyond the percentage that the central government allows rural
authorities to levy on the average income of local farmers, it
points out.
</P>
<P>
In particular the Ministry has also insisted that local
authorities stop immediately collecting four kinds of fees related
to the enrollment of children into rural schools, three kinds for
housing construction and a further three demanded when a marriage
is registered.
</P>
<P>
"All these fees are illegal and irrational and must be wiped
out. All the proceeds from levying these illegal fees must be
turned over to the treasury," the Ministry stressed.
</P>
<P>
It asks local authorities to stop imposing any new levies on
farmers until the end of 2000 and now requires them to publicize
details of fees collected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Largest Auctioneer Sells Lots Worth 51 Million Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's largest auction house
today announced that its latest auctions did business worth some
51.53 million yuan (6.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
China Guardian Auctions Company sold roughly 60 percent of its
offered lots, including the featured oil painting by Chen Yifei
called Lingering Melodies from the Xunyang River, which fetched 2.
97 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese traditional painting titled Lijiang River -
Sailing Home, created by the late renowned painter Li Keran, was
also hotly bid for at last week's auctions. A domestic businessman
paid 1.76 million yuan to obtain this master's work.
</P>
<P>
A painting by Zhang Zongcang, a well-known imperial painter of
the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), was sold for over one million yuan,
almost doubling the auctioneers' previous estimate of 550,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, four volumes of ancient books dating back to the
Southern Song Dynasty (1127-1279), aroused heated competition
among potential buyers and were finally sold for 1.76 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guardian Auctioneers also sold jewelry and ornaments without
open bidding prices, and these items also attracted many
collectors to the auctions.
</P>
<P>
The auction house also promoted a special stamp auction marking
the China 1999 World Philatelic Exhibition in August.
</P>
<P>
The company's president Wang Yannan said that she is satisfied
with the results, especially since the auction market has been
somewhat sluggish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
