<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Local Councils Start Work Amid Factional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Amid spiraling factional
struggles, Iran's first local councils officially started work on
Thursday morning with a ceremony in Tehran attended by President
Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Showing his support for the local councils, Khatami cited the
councils as a symbol of national unity and pledged to continue his
open-minded policies and to keep his promises made to the Iranian
people.
</P>
<P>
The nation should be trusted and granted freedom and an
atmosphere should be created in which people can determine their
own fate, the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Khatami as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president lashed out at his conservative opponents,
saying that there is an interpretation in which a certain group
intends to preserve special privileges for itself and to impose
its preferences on others.
</P>
<P>
This interpretation of unity will never lead to stability and
calm in the society, he said, adding that if the society is
expected to enjoy calm and comfort, people's rights should be
recognized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei said
in a message that the local councils, which are responsible for
choosing local chief administrators, should refrain from being
involved in political and factional disputes.
</P>
<P>
The involvement in any measure, which affects the unity of
council members, is harmful to the councils, he said, adding that
the council members should fully recognize their responsibilities
and make efforts to realize them.
</P>
<P>
The councils for cities, towns and villages throughout the
country held their first meetings after the Interior Ministry
rejected the latest bid by the conservatives to disqualify five
leading moderate figures from Tehran's city council.
</P>
<P>
The elections supervision committee on Monday confirmed the
result of the February 26 local elections, the first ever since
the Islamic revolution in 1979, but it nullified the elections of
five moderates, including former Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri,
a close ally of Khatami, for lacking qualifications.
</P>
<P>
The supervision committee claimed that it disqualified the five
candidates elected to Tehran city council because they had never
been approved to run for the city council.
</P>
<P>
However, the Interior Ministry replied on Wednesday that the
committee has no mandate to disqualify candidates after the poll
and warned against any move to "disturb" public opinion.
</P>
<P>
The elections for local councils were seen in Iran as a major
success for Khatami's political reforms as his supporters took
over most of the council seats throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
However, local observers noted that the disputes over the five
members of Tehran city council would further intensify the
already heated factional struggles between the moderates and the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Following their political setback in the local elections, the
conservatives, which still dominate most of the country's state
organs, will not forgo any opportunity to strengthen their
positions and marginalize the moderates, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Law on Administrative Appeals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese citizens will be entitled
to appeal against government infringement of their rights and
interests, and also against "illegal" government documents,
according to the Law on Administrative Appeals adopted today.
</P>
<P>
The 7-chapter, 43-article law will take effect on October 1
this year with a presidential decree signed by President Jiang
Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Citizens may also choose to file lawsuits with the courts if
they believe their appeals were inappropriately handled, or appeal
to a higher level of the government, as high as to the State
Council, the new law says.
</P>
<P>
These reforms represent "major breakthroughs" for China in its
effort to defend the legitimate rights and interests of the people
and demand that government bodies obey the law, observers in
Beijing said.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts pointed out that judicial review and involvement
of the highest level of government will help to abolish the
negative influence of departmentalism and local interests, and
serve to safeguard justice.
</P>
<P>
This law is also applicable to complaints raised by foreigners
and overseas organizations in China.
</P>
<P>
The law states that citizens, and companies and other
organizations may appeal against government documents if they are
considered to have caused an infringement on their legitimate
rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
All government documents can be appealed against, except those
signed by the premier, ministers, and provincial governors, which,
according to law, are subject to examination by national or local
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
Government documents were considered as laws at the time when
there was no actual legal system in China. And even today, they
remain powerful.
</P>
<P>
Legislators said in discussions that the most common complaints
of the public, such as the essentially illegal collections of
exorbitant fees by local governments, directly derive from "
illegal" and unreasonable government orders and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes these law-breaking activities on the part of certain
government employees are carried out in obedience to written
government orders, they said.
</P>
<P>
The new law allows greater convenience for those bringing
complainants, and holds government bodies accountable for
efficiency and fairness in handling complaints.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers also said that with the law on administrative
procedure, administrative punishment, and state compensation
already in place, the new legislation will further complement
China's legal system for human- rights protection, and promote
government that is "clean, honest and efficient."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tripartite Meeting on Gas Pipeline Held in Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A tripartite meeting involving
Pakistan, Turkmenistan and Afghanistan on a massive gas pipeline
project was held here Thursday with the three parties renewing
their strong commitment to the project.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Nisar Ali Khan, Pakistan's minister
for petroleum and natural resources, Batyr Sardjaev, deputy prime
minister of Turkmenistan, Redjepbai Arzov, Turkmenistan's minister
for oil, and Ahmed Jan, the Taliban official for industries and
mines.
</P>
<P>
The three parties have agreed that the 2-billion-U.S.-dollar
gas pipeline project will have an immediate positive impact on the
current situation prevailing in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration issued after the meeting said the
implementation of the project will not only help restore peace in
Afghanistan but also give an impetus to the process of the
economic revival of the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The planned 1,280-kilometer gas pipeline is designed to carry
gas to Pakistan from Turkmenistan via Afghanistan. It will connect
the Dauletabad gas field in southeastern Turkmenistan to Multan in
Pakistan's Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline, which will be 48 inches in diameter, is
designed to carry 20 billion cubic meters of gas every year.
</P>
<P>
It is the first major investment in Afghanistan in the last two
decades and will run through the west and south of the country
which is now under the Taliban's control.
</P>
<P>
"This project will definitely have long-lasting positive
effects not only for the participating countries but also for the
people of the entire region," said the joint declaration.
</P>
<P>
The three parties agreed to meet every three months to review
progress and take required decisions.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their resolve to work closely to expedite the
start of the project at the earliest time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
