<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Rebels Claim Capturing Northern Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A rebel leader in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) Thursday claimed that his forces had
captured Bondo, a town in northern DRC, driving the government
troops to flight, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Bemba, the rebel leader who is reportedly supported
by Uganda, said his Congolese Liberation Movement forces took
Bondo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that his forces had put to flight the troops loyal to
DRC President Laurent Kabila, adding that they hald taken the
smaller town of Kateke in the same area Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said that his forces would continue to
advance. "We want to control all the north of the country before
getting down to Kinshasa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bemba disclosed that he had no plans to attend a planned
Congolese national debate in Kenyan capital Nairobi next month,
dismissing it as "unrepresentative".
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led rebels who were allegedly supported by Rwanda and
Uganda took up arms against Kabila early last August and now hold
much of the east and the north of the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Bemba emerged at the head of a separate group in the north
later. Another rebel leader is Chairman of the main rebel
movement Congolese Democratic Coalition, Wamba dia Wamba, a former
professor in a Tanzanian university. 
</P>
