<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States announced a major shift in economic
sanctions policy Wednesday that will permit American firms to sell
food and medicine to Iran, Sudan and Libya, three countries listed
by the State Department as "sponsors of international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
-- As the pace quickened in the search for a diplomatic
solution to the five-week-old Balkan crisis, U.S. Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott said Wednesday that the United States and
its allies are close to agreement with Russia on the key issue of
an international peacekeeping force for Kosovo, the focus of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Richard Ashby, the U.S. Marine pilot acquitted of
manslaughter in the Italian cable-car accident that killed 20
people, went on trial on obstruction of justice charges stemming
from the destruction of videotape shot from the cockpit of his jet.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. House issued a sharp challenge to President Bill
Clinton, voting 249 to 180, to bar him from sending ground troops
to Yugoslavia without Congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Russia reached an
agreement on a 4.6-billion-U.S.-dollar loan and a new economic
plan to help keep the country afloat for the moment.
</P>
<P>
-- Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) leaders decided not
to declare a Palestinian state May 4 and to postpone the decision
until after Israel's May 17 elections. 
</P>
