<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Thailand Vow to Expand Trade and Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China and Thailand have agreed to
expand mutual trade and investment, saying it will benefit both
economies in the wake of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting here today with Zeng Peiyan, minister in
charge of the State Development Planning Commission, visiting Thai
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said that Thailand hopes to increase
exports to China and that more Chinese investments would come to
his country.
</P>
<P>
Stricken by the economic crisis last year, Thailand's economy
declined 7.8 percent in 1998, but is now well on the road to
recovery. Thailand is expected to have an economic growth rate of
close to one percent this year, said the Thai prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Thailand supports China's early entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO) this year, saying this will help
build a better world trade system.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that China was also hit hard by the economic crisis
last year, resulting in a decline of exports and a sluggish
domestic market. He said an increase of trade and investment
between China and Thailand will benefit both countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister and Zeng also exchanged ideas on the
possibility of establishing two joint ventures, one a paper-pulp
mill and the other a potash fertilizer plant, in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with Chuan today, Yu Xiaosong, president
of the China Council for the Promotion of International Trade (
CCPIT), said he anticipates that more Chinese investors will come
to Thailand, as China recently simplified procedures for overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between China and Thailand hit 3.515 billion U.
S. dollars in 1997, with China importing 2.015 billion U.S.
dollars of Thai goods and exporting 1.5 billion U.S. dollars worth
of Chinese goods to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to Thailand plummeted 23.5 percent last year as
a result of the Asian financial crisis, reaching only 1.148
billion U.S. dollars. At the same time, however, Thai exports to
China surged 19.8 percent to 2.413 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter this year saw an increase in both imports and
exports between China and Thailand. China's exports to Thailand
topped 267 million U.S. dollars, up 6.7 percent, and imports from
Thailand were 583 million U.S. dollars, up 13.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
