<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Details Added Chinese Legislature Rejects Draft Amendments to Highway Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Planned reforms of China's
Highway Law which would have replaced existing road tolls with
fuel taxes have been rejected because of fears they could place
extra financial burdens on the country's farmers which the central
government has pledged to ease.
</P>
<P>
However, it was a close run issue with only one vote tipping
the balance when China's top legislative body, the Standing
Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), met today
to consider the draft amendments.
</P>
<P>
The legislature rejected the draft amendments proposed by the
State Council for fear that it could result in unjustifiable
burdens on farmers.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were drawn up by the State Council but of the 125
members of the NPC Standing Committee present at the meeting, 77
voted for, six voted against the draft law, and 42 abstained.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, with a total of 154 members of the
Standing Committee, 78 votes are required to have a bill approved.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers were generally in favor of such a reform,
believing it would help reduce the random and sometime exorbitant
fees collected along the country's highways.
</P>
<P>
However, they also agreed that if it was adopted farmers would
have to pay out more for using farm machines, which obviously need
fuel, and this would put a heavier economic burden on their
already difficult finances.
</P>
<P>
According to officials with the NPC Standing Committee, the
State Council attached great importance to the opinions of the
legislators. After preliminary discussions of the law last year,
the government formed a special investigation team to improve and
refine their reform plan.
</P>
<P>
However, at this session of the NPC meeting, many legislators
still aired their worries and concerns that the problem has not
been completely solved.
</P>
<P>
The legislature said that it will advise the State Council to
further revise the reform plan and table the draft law for further
discussions at future legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
"The failure to pass the draft law today was an indication that
the lawmakers are very earnest and responsible, and China's
legislation is democratic," an official with NPC Standing
Committee said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, this was the second draft law that
the national legislature has rejected in the last decade. The
first was focused on urban neighborhood committees during the term
of office of the Seventh NPC Standing Committee (1988-1993).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
