<HEADLINE> S. Africa Prepares for All Africa Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has started
preparing the 7th All Africa Games due to be taking place in
Johannesburg between September 10 and 19, the Star newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Danie Malan, chief executive officer of the Games, said at a
function in Johannesburg Wednesday that the organizing committee
would try to make the All Africa Games the biggest and best of its
kind in African continent.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a failed bid to host the Olympics, Malan said: "we
are determined to show the prophets of doom that South Africa can
succeed."
</P>
<P>
"Once these All Africa Games have proven successful, doors will
open for future Olympic bids, and South Africa's hopes of hosting
the 2006 World Cup (soccer) finals will have been given a
tremendous boost," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malan also quoted economists as saying that the Games would
boost the economy of South Africa to the tune of three billion
rand (500 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Amalgamated Banks of South Africa (ABSA) announced at the
party that it would be launching some 15 initiatives over the
coming weeks to create awareness of the important sport event
among the general public.
</P>
<P>
"The All Africa Games are the Olympics of Africa, but the
average man on the street does not see them this way, and we aim
to change that perception, " said Brendan O'Donnell, ABSA's
marketing and sales general manager.
</P>
<P>
As part of the company's campaign, ABSA will be publishing a
comprehensive information booklet in mid-August which will contain
details on every aspect of the event, including maps, venues,
timetables and competition schedules.
</P>
<P>
Also the banking group will purchase two of the units in the
athletes' village overlooking the Alexandra black township, the
village will become a low-cost housing development after the
Games, and all competitors will have a chance to win one. 
</P>
