<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stop Air Strikes, Start Talks on Balkans, Says Russian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A halt to NATO's air strikes is
the main condition for the start of negotiations to solve the
Balkan crisis, Russian president's Kosovo envoy Viktor
Chernomyrdin said here Thursday before boarding a plane for Bonn
on a two-day mediation mission in Germany, Italy and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Yugoslav government has agreed to an
international presence in Kosovo under the U.N. auspices and
widely joined by Russia, while preparing a phased withdrawal of
Serbian troops from Kosovo and to grant broad autonomy to the
province.
</P>
<P>
It is now time for NATO to take effective measures, and, above
all, to stop air strikes against Yugoslavia, Chernomyrdin
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he was taking to Bonn and Rome "concrete
proposals about solving the Balkan crisis which have been agreed
on with the president (Boris Yeltsin)."
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Ambassador to Russia Borislav Milosevic, who saw
Chernomyrdin off at the airport, said Belgrade allows the entry
into Kosovo of an observation team composed of civil servants
under the U.N. flag and with wide Russian presence.
</P>
<P>
He cited Belarus, India, Cyprus and Argentina as well as
African and other Latin American countries as among those that can
send representatives to the observation team. But he said NATO
members countries involved in the bombing of Yugoslavia must be
kept off the team, stressing that the constitution of the U.N.
team must be approved by the Yugoslav government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
