<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Prime Minister Leaves for Official Visit to United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi left here Thursday evening for a week-long visit to the
United States for talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on
economic issues and global affairs.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which will take Obuchi to Los Angeles, Chicago and
Washington, is the first official visit to the United States by a
Japanese prime minister in 12 years, although Japanese prime
ministers often make working trips to the country.
</P>
<P>
Economic issues are expected to be a major topic of the summit
between Obuchi and Clinton scheduled for Monday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi plans to explain Japan's efforts to achieve its avowed
target of 0.5 percent economic growth in the current fiscal year,
but Washington, which is skeptical of Japan's economic recovery,
is expected to push for further stimulus measures, Japanese
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda of their talks are security issues,
including the updated Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines,
under which Japan will provide new military support to U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are also expected to reaffirm the importance of
maintaining close cooperation among Japan, South Korea and the
United States in dealing with the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK), the officials said.
</P>
<P>
On Kosovo, Obuchi will explain Japan's efforts in helping
refugees fleeing the war-torn Yugoslav province, including a fresh
aid package expected to be announced next week, the officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
