<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Refutes Report of Rift With Rwanda in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Defense Ministry has
refuted the media reports that Rwandan army had recently killed 11
Ugandan soldiers deployed in eastern part of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Barigye Ba-hoku, press assistant to State Minister of Defense
Steven Kavuma, told Xinhua in a telephone interview Thursday
morning that the reports are purely fabrication.
</P>
<P>
He said:"We do not have any rift with our Rwandan friends in
the DRC. It must be part of Kabila's propaganda work. If we have
any rift with each other, we would not be together there."
</P>
<P>
The New Vision Thursday also reported that the Rwandan
authorities denied killing Ugandan troops in the DRC. It quoted
Rwanda Army Spokesman Emmanuel Ndahiro as describing the report as
groundless.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor daily Thursday said that Leon Kasonga, spokesman
for the Congolese Armed Forces, had told state television that the
Rwandan troops had opened fire on Ugandan soldiers in Camp Ketele
in the rebel-held third city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are said to back the rebellion aimed at
ousting President Laurent Kabila and they deployed troops in
eastern DRC, allegedly for the sake of their borders' safety.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports from time to time on the alleged rift
between Rwandan and Ugandan troops there. But these reports have
all been refuted by army authorities of the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
