<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Ruler Begins Valedictory Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalami Abubakar has commenced a nationwide valedictory tour
of military installations before the scheduled hand-over of power
to a democratically- elected civil government on May 29.
</P>
<P>
Addressing military personnel and police officers in Ibadan,
capital of Oyo State, he stressed the need for military men to
subordinate themselves to civil leadership as they go back to the
barracks, The Post Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The head of state said that it was desirable for the military
to go back to the barracks, detach themselves from politics and
face their assignments as defined in the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar noted that "during the cold war period, the military
received supports, but now no new military government will enjoy
any support locally and internationally," adding the era of
coup-making was gone for ever.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, he announced that the various special task
forces set up by his administration would all be disbanded by the
end of May and their members sent back to the barracks. 
</P>
