<HEADLINE> Britain to Take in 2nd Group of Refugees, But Only 160 in Number </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A second group of ethnic Albanian
refugees from Kosovo is due to arrive in Britain from Macedonia
later Thursday, but consisting of only 160 people, press reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The 160 people, including some 20 children, are to be housed in
two refugee centers in central England.
</P>
<P>
Although Prime Minster Tony Blair has said repeatedly that
NATO's bombing on Yugoslavia was intended to save the refugees,
they were actually pouring out of Kosovo only after the air
strikes began.
</P>
<P>
Since the air strikes began a month ago, hundreds of thousands
of refugees have been on exodus from Kosovo, with Britain only
taking in its first wave of 161 people last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, Sadako Ogata, has
urged Britain to harbor more of the refugees who have overwhelmed
the meager resources of neighboring countries like Macedonia and
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Liberal Democrats have criticized the government for
little action on receiving refugees, noting that Germany has
already taken in 10,000 refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
