<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Increase Share in African Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's equity share in the
African Development Bank (ADB) will be increased in the immediate
future to demonstrate its commitment to the development of the
African economies, according to a senior Nigerian official.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of an international workshop here
Wednesday, National Planning Minister Chief Rasheed Gbadamosi said
that if Nigeria increases its equity in ADB, it would serve as a
better and surer way of establishing some influence on the African
scene, This Day newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted at the workshop on the ADB that "the
much-touted perception of Nigeria as the giant of Africa can only
be realized through its contributions and influence in
sub-regional and regional organizations such as ECOWAS (Economic
Community of West African States) Fund and ADB".
</P>
<P>
At present, Nigeria is the largest African shareholder with
about 10 percent equity. African owners have 60 percent equity
shares of the ADB while non-Africans control the remaining 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Besides its substantial equity in the ADB, Nigeria also
established the Nigerian Trust Fund in 1976 with a resource base
of more than 400 million U. S. dollars managed by the ADB to
provide assistance to needy African countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the ADB group has demonstrated its
commitment to the development of African economies, having
committed 2.7 billion dollars to 28 projects and studies in
Nigeria between 1986 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Gbadamosi noted that the continued emphasis by the ADB on
economic integration within the framework of African Policy Reform
will provide an important market outlet for Nigeria's industrial
products.
</P>
<P>
"There is a potential for expanding Nigeria's industrial
capacity to meet the additional demand that will result from
regional economic integration," he added.
</P>
<P>
ADB member countries are expected to converge in Cairo on May
25 this year to work out modalities for increasing working capital
by 35 percent from 21 million dollars to 28.5 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
