<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold Another Provincial Council Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will hold elections to
the Southern Provincial Council (SPC) on June 10 following polls
to six provincial councils early this year, the Commissioner of
Elections announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"There are 707 candidates in the contest to compete for 55
seats including two bonus seats," said Commissioner Dayananda
Dissanayake.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for the SPC closed at noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ten recognized political parties and nine independent groups
are contesting in the polls to the provincial council which
consists of the three districts of Galle, Matara and Hambantota.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the main battle will be fought between the
ruling People's Alliance (PA) and the main opposition United
National Party (UNP), while the People's Liberation Front or
Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna (JVP) will pose as the third force.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka held the North Western Provincial Council elections
on January 25, with the PA beating the UNP with a big margin.
</P>
<P>
On April 6, the PA swept the polls in the Western, North
Central, Central, Uva and Sabaragamuwa provincial councils,
defeating the UNP with a small margin. However, the JVP staged a
comeback with 15 seats in the five provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
