<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds Up Offshore Natural Gas Development(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China is stepping up efforts to
develop offshore natural gas in the country's coastal areas, in a
bid to adjust its energy structure and increase the supply of
clean and high-quality energy for the developed coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhao Xiuguang, a senior official with the China
National Offshore Oil Corp. (CNOOC), Shanghai and the provinces of
Guangdong, Fujian, Zhejiang, and Jiangsu are the most economically
vibrant coastal regions in China, with a 13 to 19 percent annual
increase on average in their GDPs, far exceeding the national
average.
</P>
<P>
Their combined energy demand will top 360 million tons of coal
by the year 2000, 470 million tons by 2005, and 610 million tons
by 2010, said the expert, stressing that developing offshore
natural gas is important for sustained economic growth in the
region.
</P>
<P>
However, for a long time, the use of coal has caused problems
for the environment and transport in coastal areas, and it should
be replaced as a matter of some urgency with clean and efficient
natural gas to meet the needs of continued economic expansion, the
expert said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China is very rich in offshore natural gas
reserves, and the country has developed a group of important gas
production centers in the South China Sea, Bohai Sea and the East
China Sea.
</P>
<P>
The official explained that the western part of the South China
Sea is a key gas source and four gas fields and 15 gas-bearing
structures have been found there.
</P>
<P>
The Nanyacheng 13-1 gas field off the island province of Hainan
now provides 2.9 billion cu m of natural gas for the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region annually via a 780-km sub-sea
pipeline, and 500 million cu m of gas for the province's
fertilizer plants and power plants via a 100-km pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that the western sea area of the South China Sea will
add three billion cu m of gas by year 2005, and another three
billion cu m by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds Up Offshore Natural Gas Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the Bohai Sea, one gas field and 18 gas-bearing structures
have been discovered. The Jinzhou 20-2 gas field provides 400
million cu m of natural gas for the Jinzhou Chemical Fertilizer
Plant annually and will increase the supply to 700 million cu m by
2010. 
</P>
