<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Central Council Delays Decision on Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA CITY, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Central Council has decided to postpone making
a final decision on the declaration of an independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
In a statement adopted in Thursday's session, the council
decided to reconvene meeting in June, after Israel's May 27
elections, and make its final decision on the statehood issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said, the council has decided to form
committees charged with preparation works for statehood, such as
formulating the constitution and election laws.
</P>
<P>
The council strongly criticized Israel for not implementing the
sighed agreements with the Palestinians and for its expansion of
Jewish settlements, demolition of Palestinians' homes, and
confiscation of their lands in the occupied territories, it said.
</P>
<P>
The council has authorized the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) and other Palestinian institutions to take proper measures
to react to those Israeli policies, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On the peace process, it said that moving the peace process
forward is the national policy of the Palestinian people and they
will continue the peace talks with Israel under signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The statement denounced the Israeli government's decision to
close several Palestinian offices in the Orient House in East
Jerusalem, saying those offices are absolutely legal.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed thanks to those countries which have
voiced their support to the Palestinian people's right of
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the statement mentioned the United States for
its recent policy towards the peace process.
</P>
<P>
It thanked U.S. President Bill Clinton for his letter to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in which he called for
accelerated Israel-Palestinian final-status talks to be concluded
within a year and for his recognization of the Palestinian
people's right of self-determination.
</P>
<P>
The council also expressed its thanks to Sheikh Ahmed Yassin,
the spiritual leader of the radical Palestinian Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas), saying his participation in the council meeting
as an observer represented a big step forward in the direction of
national reconciliation, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed the importance of legal constructions of
various national institutions and the formulation of laws.
</P>
<P>
The 124-member council on Tuesday started discussing the issue
on whether to declare an independent Palestinian state on May 4,
when the five-year transitional period stipulated in the 1993 Oslo
accords expires.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has stated many times in the past that he has the right
to do so under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
But Israel opposes the idea, threatening to annex parts of
the West Bank now under its control if the Palestinians take
unilateral steps in this respect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
