<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A rally in resources stocks was
not enough to drag the Australian sharemarket into positive
territory Friday as major industrial shares slid lower.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the market continued to trade on sentiment created
Wednesday by inflation figures that appeared to dash hopes of an
interest rate cut in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index fell 17.8 points to 3,104.9,
down from an intra-day high of 3,127.4 points.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian sharemarket has seen another bout of
profit-taking with most larger shares moving lower," said Morgan
Stockbroking's Simon Reed.
</P>
<P>
The slide in the all ordinaries came despite an initial brief
move higher at the open after the Dow Jones Industrial average
picked up a slight 13.74 points to 10,845.45 for its second
consecutive closing high.
</P>
<P>
Most of the positive action in the Australian market was
confined to the resources sector.
</P>
<P>
While the all resources index rose 28.3 points to 1,200.9, the
all industrials index shed 61.4 points to 5,479.9.
</P>
<P>
Resource giant BHP raced 42 cents or 2.6 per cent higher to
16.58 Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto surged 62.5
cents to 25.79 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate sensitive banking sector was again lower but
performing a little better than Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank offloaded 9.6 cents to 29.61 Australian
dollars and Westpac bank eased 11 cents to 11.77 Australian
dollars, while ANZ bank slid 4.3 cents to 12.20 Australian dollars
and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia was steady at 27.95
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the resources sector, the gold index added 9.1
points to close at 993.2.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Thursday afternoon was
282.55 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared to a close of 282.70
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 515.46 million stocks traded for a value
of 993.32 million Australian dollars. Falling stocks outnumbered
rising stocks by 769 to 675 and 502 stocks remained steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
