Wednesday for making public declarations contrary to the
government stand and for "harming the prestige of the government."
Immediately after that, the Serb Socialist Party of President
Slobodan Milosevic said it was ready to accept "a UN mission" in
Kosovo. It did not specify the nature of such a mission, but
stressed that an approval by the Yugoslav government is a
precondition.
</P>
<P>
-- The war of Kosovo is playing not only in the sky of
Yugoslavia, but also within the wall of the Kremlin and in the
subtle combinations of the political checkerboard of the old
Russia. The nomination of former Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin -- who is a "dove" -- as the his envoy to Belgrade by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin was clearly a counter-offensive by
Yeltsin against the "hawks" led by Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. 
