<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Real Estate Prices Slightly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's real estate prices
dropped slightly in the first quarter this year, according to an
official survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
The survey jointly conducted by the State Development Planning
Commission and the National Bureau of Statistics in 35 major
cities found that the average real estate price dropped by 0.3
percent in the first three months from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Nanning, capital of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in
south China recorded the most drastic drop of 10.6 percent, while
the highest price gains were reported in Yinchuan, capital of
midwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, where the real
estate price was 9.8 percent up year on year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent drop in the general price level, the survey
said real estate costs are still far beyond the income level of
ordinary Chinese, which has resulted in a sluggish market.
</P>
<P>
The cost of land was 2.5 percent up in the first three months
on a yearly basis, but was 0.4 percent down from the fourth
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The survey said the drop in land costs was partly due to the
downward adjustment of land prices by some regional governments in
support of residential housing development.
</P>
<P>
The rental price of residential houses, offices and hotels
declined by 3.4 percent, four percent and 7.4 percent,
respectively, while that of industrial houses and warehouses was 0.
2 percent up, producing a 4.4 percent fall in the general level of
house rents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
