<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Slows Down Nuclear Power Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China will not start any new
nuclear power projects within three years, a high-ranking nuclear
industry official has announced.
</P>
<P>
The decision has been taken in a bid to cope with decreasing
demand for power supplies as a result, mainly, of the negative
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"There has also been under capacity at a number of large state-
owned enterprises," said Shen Wenquan, director of the Nuclear
Power Department under the China Nuclear Industry Corp., at the
Third International Nuclear Power Industry Exhibition which ended
here today.
</P>
<P>
Shen also pointed to low prices which are hindering nuclear
power development in the country. China has relied on
international cooperation for key nuclear power equipment and
related technology, and that has increased the cost of nuclear
power, pushing its price to a much higher level than that of both
thermal and hydro-electric power.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three years, Shen said, China will focus on
upgrading its existing power grids and eliminating excessive small
thermal power plants that are badly equipped and cause pollution,
in a bid to enhance power quality and returns.
</P>
<P>
"However, this does not mean bleak prospects for nuclear power
development in China," Shen noted, adding that the decline in
demand for electric power is just temporary and that there will
conversely be a shortage of power for quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
"Both domestic and overseas investors should not lose sight of
a great potential market demand for nuclear power in this country,
" Shen said. "Be patient and far-sighted."
</P>
<P>
At present, China has two nuclear power stations under
commercial operation, the Qinshan Nuclear Power Station of east
China's Zhejiang Province and the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station
in south China's Guangdong Province, with total electric
production of 12 billion kwh and 50 billion kwh, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the second and third phases of Qinshan and
Ling'ao nuclear power stations and Lianyungang Nuclear Power Plant
are in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that by the year 2006, when all the projects
are completed, nuclear power will contribute about three percent
of China's total power output, some two percentage points more
than the present figure, but still much lower than the world
average of 17 percent, and an even bigger gap to that of developed
countries like the United States, France and Japan.
</P>
<P>
China's State Development Planning Commission is now working
out an overall nuclear power development plan, aiming to bring the
country's nuclear power generating capacity up to 20 million
kilowatts by 2010, and 40 million kilowatts by 2020, accounting
for five percent of the country's total power production.
</P>
<P>
Over a dozen provinces, such as Shandong, Fujian, Hainan,
Jiangxi, Hunan, Hubei and Sichuan, have all been active in making
preparations for building their own nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
One of them, Shandong, has already selected a site for four
generating units each with installed capacity of one million
kilowatts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
