<HEADLINE> Japan's Opposition Leader, Upper House Chief Leave for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Head of Japan's largest opposition
Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) Naoto Kan and Juro Saito,
president of the House of Councilors (upper house), left Japan
Thursday for China, each leading a delegation.
</P>
<P>
Kan and his party left Kansai airport in Osaka Prefecture,
western Japan, for Shanghai, where he will discuss the
stabilization of Asia's financial and monetary situation with
economic specialists, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, his first to China since the DPJ absorbed
three other parties last April, Kan intends to build individual
connections with Chinese leaders, Kyodo quoted DPJ party officials
as saying.
</P>
<P>
After traveling to Xi'an in China's northwest Shaanxi Province,
Kan is scheduled to arrive in Beijing next Monday.
</P>
<P>
While in Beijing, Kan is expected to meet with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, Vice President Hu Jintao and Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan to exchange opinions on acknowledging events
in the recent history of Japan and China, the updated Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation guidelines and other regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Upper House chief Saito, is expected to hold talks
with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), and
other Chinese leaders in Beijing. He will visit other Chinese
cities, including Shanghai and Chongqing. 
</P>
