<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Experts Call For Efforts for Rapid Agricultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Economists of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) Thursday called for greater efforts by the
Asian economies to prod rapid agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
In a study of rural Asia conducted by the ADB and presented
during a seminar on the eve of the bank's 32nd annual meeting, the
economists said that the public sector of economies has to play a
key role in this process.
</P>
<P>
"Agricultural growth is dependent on a regulatory environment
and levels of investment in agricultural research and rural
infrastructure that the private sector has insufficient incentive
to provide," they said.
</P>
<P>
In the study titled "Rural Asia: Beyond the Green Revolution,"
the economists suggested investments in agricultural research and
extension to provide a continuous stream of yield-enhancing
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Investments in rural infrastructure, especially irrigation,
roads and electricity are also important factors in agricultural
growth, they said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, attention should be paid to investments in the
education, nutrition, and health of rural people to increase their
productivities, they said.
</P>
<P>
Efficient rural financial markets are also important to provide
a broad range of financial services at minimal transaction costs
to the rural population, they said.
</P>
<P>
The economists believed that a key challenge for policy makers
is to continue to promote rapid growth in rural areas while at the
same time making growth more pro-poor and keeping management of
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
In retrospect, the economists said that rural Asia has
undergone an unprecedented technological and economic revolution
in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
The revolution "has dramatically improved the region's food
security, reduced poverty, and raised incomes," they said.
</P>
<P>
This transformation was initiated by the green revolution in
agriculture, the expression of the application of modern science
to Asia's agriculture problems, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
