<HEADLINE> China Condemns NATO Bombing of Yugoslav TV Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- NATO's wanton bombing of a
Yugoslav TV station, which killed and wounded dozens of its staffs,
constituted a particularly severe violation of relevant
international conventions and ethical standards, said a Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman here today.
</P>
<P>
Sun Yuxi made the remarks at a regular press conference where
he was asked to comment on the recent bombing of the Serb TV
Station.
</P>
<P>
"The bombing intruded seriously into the basic human rights
and freedom," Sun said, adding that NATO's continuing military
strikes against Yugoslavia has caused a great deal of property
losses and human casualties.
</P>
<P>
Such acts have aroused strong condemnation from all peace
proponents including Chinese people, he said, adding that "the
Chinese government has always held a consistent and clear attitude
toward the issue of Kosovo, which I have repeatedly addressed here.
"
</P>
<P>
"We have particularly called for an immediate stop to the
airstrikes against Yugoslavia," he stressed. 
</P>
