<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three New Banks Licensed in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya has
licensed three new banks which will start their operations at any
time.
</P>
<P>
The three news banks are the Majestic Bank, Mesacom Bank and
K-Rep Bank. One of them is converted from a micro finance
non-governmental organization, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A central bank source said the banks were licensed in March but
are yet to meet the statutory capital requirements of 200 million
shillings (some 3.1 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All the three banks were locally-owned and had met most of the
requirements, the source added.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, the banks are beefing up their capital
bases to 500 million shillings as required by the new regulations
of the central bank which demand that existing commercial banks
need to raise their statutory capital base to 500 million
shillings by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The licensing of the three banks brings the number of
commercial banks to 59 in Kenya nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Last year, five local banks collapsed due to liquidity problems
while the government stepped in to save the National Bank of
Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
