<HEADLINE> Former Ugandan President to Return Home From Exile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Ugandan President Milton
Obote is allowed to return home soon from his exiled life in
Zambia where he has been living since he was ousted in a coup in
July 1985 by an army led by President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Monitor daily reported that the cabinet made the
dramatic decision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Obote, who is an outspoken critic of President Museveni, was
allowed to come back on grounds that he agreed to drop all his
previous political conditions for returning to Uganda and to
retire from politics.
</P>
<P>
He previously demanded Museveni to step down from power and
some constitutional article to be dropped if he should come back.
</P>
<P>
Once returning to Uganda, Obote, who is president of Uganda
People's Congress, shall be given security, and enjoy all the
benefits provided for a former head of state under the 1995
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted minister in charge of Presidency Ruhakana
Rugunda as saying that Obote will be able to vote in the
referendum.  
</P>
