<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worst May Be Over for East Asian Crisis: Singapore PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong said Thursday that the worst may be over for the East
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Goh said this while addressing the U.S. Economic Strategy
Institute's Annual Global Economy Conference in Washington D.C.
via videoconferencing this morning.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is optimistic about that as there are signs of
recovery in the East Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
The financial markets in the region, as well as the foreign
rates, have stabilized, Goh said, adding that interest rates have
also returned to pre-crisis levels and confidence in the Asian
stock market is regaining.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the region will bounce back if all
countries hit by the crisis succeed in correcting the structural
flaws in their economies
</P>
<P>
"I believe the region will emerge from the crisis stronger,"
said Goh.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. to lead in keeping the global trading
system open as the move will lead to more economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"This will help Asia recover, and in turn, Asia will regain
quickly its status as a major growing market for the U.S., setting
in motion a virtuous cycle," Goh noted.
</P>
<P>
He also called for China to be admitted early as a member of the
World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
He said this will open up the huge Chinese market and ensure
that China becomes a responsible member of the international
trading community.
</P>
<P>
"In November this year, the Third WTO Ministerial Meeting in
Seattle will consider the launch of a new round of multilateral
trade negotiations," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Seattle will be an important crossroads for trade
liberalization and globalization," he said.
</P>
<P>
Goh also urged Japan, which he said is the region's largest
economy and the key to Asia's recovery, to open its market wider.
</P>
<P>
"If Japan recovers and opens up its markets, the Asian recovery
will be speeded up," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Strategy Institute (ESI) is a private non-profit,
non-partisan public policy research organization based in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
ESI focuses on globalization and its effects, and shapes opinion
and strategy by publishing books, articles and editorials as well
as by providing testimony to the U.S. Congress and private
consultation to the U.S. government and business leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
