<HEADLINE> HK Media Worry About Influx of 1.67m Mainlanders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong newspapers Thursday
in editorials or commentaries expressed their worries about the
consequences of the influx of 1.67 million mainlanders to Hong
Kong if the Court of Final appeal Ruling on right of abode is
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Regina Ip, secretary for Security, announced Wednesday that
more than 1.67 million people from the mainland are eligible to
live in Hong Kong following a controversial court ruling.
</P>
<P>
According to Ip, the figure can be underestimated because
mainland children of former Hong Kong residents who had migrated
or died were not included. Also wives of Hong Kong residents
still in the mainland were continuing to have children so the
number of people eligible for the right of abode will increase.
</P>
<P>
The papers said that it will bring a heavy burden to the Hong
Kong society.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po said in an editorial that under the circumstances of
its downward economy, a rising unemployment rate and large
financial budget, it is hard for the Hong Kong society to cope
with such a problem. Hong Kong has currently a population of
nearly 7 million.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary, Ta Kung Pao described the figure released by
the government as shocking.
</P>
<P>
It said such a large number of mainlanders to Hong Kong will
directly affect its social stability, economic recovery and long-
term development in the future.
</P>
<P>
The right of abode issue should be solved in accordance with
the articles of the Basic Law, it said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily said in a commentary that most of
mainlanders who are eligible to live in Hong Kong according to the
court ruling are not competent professionals and they will surely
exert tremendous impacts on a wide range of areas of housing,
medical and health work, education and social welfare in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong media also made some suggestions to properly
settle the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
