<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Local Councils Start Work Amid Factional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Amid spiraling factional
struggles, Iran's first local councils officially started work on
Thursday morning with a ceremony in Tehran attended by President
Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The councils for cities, towns and villages throughout the
country held their first meetings after the Interior Ministry
rejected the latest bid by the conservatives to disqualify five
leading moderate figures from Tehran's city council.
</P>
<P>
The elections supervision committee on Monday confirmed the
result of the February 26 local elections, the first ever since
the Islamic revolution in 1979, but it nullified the elections of
five moderates, including former Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri,
a close ally of Khatami, for lacking qualifications.
</P>
<P>
However, the moderate Interior Ministry replied on Wednesday
that the committee has no mandate to disqualify candidates after
the poll and warned against any move to "disturb" public opinion.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, any attempt aimed at disturbing public opinion
will have the least effect on determination of the (Iranian)
Muslim people and those who are serving the people within the
government," it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry argued that the committee has no authority to defy
the qualification of the five elected after the five-member
arbitration committee, appointed jointly by President Khatami and
Majlis (parliament) Speaker Nateq Nouri, ruled that they are
eligible for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The supervision committee had attempted to bar some moderate
supporters of President Khatami, including the five, from running
the councils, but was forced to back down following the
intervention of Khatami and the arbitrary committee hours before
the elections.
</P>
<P>
The elections for local councils were seen in Iran as a major
success for Khatami's political reforms as his supporters took
over most of the council seats throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
However, local observers noted that the disputes over the five
members of Tehran city council would further intensify the
already heated factional struggles between the moderates and the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Following their political setback in the local elections, the
conservatives, which still dominate most of the country's state
organs, will not forgo any opportunity to strengthen their
positions and marginalize the moderates, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
