<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery of Earlier Fossil Man in China Hopeful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YUXI, YUNNAN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The conclusion that human
was originated in Africa should not be final and earlier fossil
man may be found in China, according to Chinese archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
"We're expecting some new and exciting discoveries, that is,
the discovery of the oldest fossil man ever found in China," said
Mr. Jin Changzhu, director of the Zhoukoudian International
Research Center of Paleoanthropology at the Seventh Annual Meeting
of the China Society of Vertebrate Paleozoology here in Yuxi,
Yunnan Province, on the eve of the '99 International Horticultural
Exposition scheduled to open in Kunming on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists have started a new round of excavation
in Fanchang County of east China's Anhui Province with the hope to
find much earlier fossil man.
</P>
<P>
"If we find fossil man dated back more than two million years
ago or even earlier in China," said Qiu Zhuding, head of the
Institute of Vertebrate Paleozoology and Palaeoanthropology under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, "it will touch off another round
of debate on the place of origin of man."
</P>
<P>
During their last excavation in Fanchang at the end of last
year, Chinese anthropologists found fossils of advanced primates
and stone- and bone-ware suspected of artificial manufacture dated
back to more than 2 - 2.5 million years ago, the first such
discoveries along the lower reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Major breakthrough has also been made in the excavation efforts
in the Three Gorges area on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River,
where the world's largest water conservancy and hydropower project,
the Three Gorges Dam, is under construction. The discoveries will
provide the basis for establishing whether Wushan Man ever existed
in China more than two million years ago.
</P>
<P>
A currently dominant theory in the world holds that man was
originated in Africa and started to move to other parts of the
world some two million years ago.
</P>
<P>
This theory also describes the origin of man as the result of
the emergence of the Great Rift Valley of Africa, which
drastically changed the living environment of anthropoid and
forced them to evolve into a higher stage.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Ye Jie, president of the China Society of
Vertebrate Paleozoology, the rise of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau
also created a natural environment very similar to that in ancient
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"China is one of the few countries in the world blessed with
the richest fossil resources and living things in each historical
period have representative fossils," Ye said. "There is great
possibility to find fossil man of much earlier periods."
</P>
<P>
China has discovered the world's oldest fossils of advanced
primates, including those dated back to nearly 40 million years
ago, anthropoid at Lufeng dated back to eight million years ago
and Yuanmou fossil man in Yunnan dated back to some 1.7 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the annual meeting were unanimous that the
conclusion that man was originated in Africa should not be final,
because fossil study shows that some of the features of Peking man
have inheritance relations with those of modern man.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
