<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Unveils Immigration Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Australian Immigration Minister
Philip Ruddock said Thursday Australia's migrant intake would rise
by 2,000 to 82,000 in the fiscal year of 1999-2000 following
drastic cuts in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Ruddock said the government had responded to calls by industry,
local governments for more skilled migrants by earmarking a
"contingency reserve" of 5,000 skilled places if they were needed.
</P>
<P>
The 1999-2000 fiscal year humanitarian program remained stable
at 12,000, which included about 10,000 places for overseas
applicants from places like the former Yugoslavia, he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The non-humanitarian program had been set at 70,000 places, up
from 68,000 in the current fiscal year, which ends on June 30, he
said.
</P>
<P>
There were 32,000 places for family reunions, 35,000 places for
skilled migrants and 3,000 in a special eligibility category.
</P>
<P>
Liberal member of the ruling Australian Liberal Party and
business groups have been calling for increased intake of
immigrants to boost the country's economy, while some are against
such increase on employment and environmental grounds.
</P>
<P>
Australians needed to spread the word to families, friends, and
employees about the need for more immigration, given Australia's
aging population and declining fertility rate, Jeff Kennett,
premier of Australia's second richest state Victoria, told radio
3AW.
</P>
<P>
The Victorian government has called for skilled migration
levels to be more than doubled in a bid to increase Australia's
population to 28 million by 2060 from 18 million in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
