<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 07:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Banks' Assets Grow in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Total assets of Lebanese banks
rose to 36.9 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this
year, an increase of 16 percent compared with 31.1 billion dollars
in the same period in 1998, the Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The consolidated balance sheets of commercial banks rose 0.73
percent in March compared with 0.16 percent in February,
indicating that average banking growth is unlikely to exceed 20
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank expects net profits of banks to reach 126
million dollars in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits in the first quarter rose to 31.2 billion
dollars compared with 26.4 billion dollars in the same period last
year. In 1998, total deposits stood at 30.5 billion dollars, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese pound deposits represent 34.4 percent of the total
deposits while foreign currency deposits, mainly in U.S. dollars,
stood at 17.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Iskandar, regional manager of Thomson BankWatch, an
international rating company, said Lebanese banks are still
achieving good growth.
</P>
<P>
"An annual growth rate of 10-11 percent is still good. This
means that banks are still growing but not at the rate of previous
years,"Iskandar said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the balance sheets of the banks went up by 22.07
percent over 1997. But bankers doubts that local banks will be
able to match that performance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Banks must start looking for other means beside deposits to
sustain growth," Iskandar said.
</P>
<P>
Among Lebanon's 80 banks, the top 30 have 30 percent of their
assets in Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
Iskandar said that banks must develop their balance sheets
rather than count on deposits and put them in government Treasury
bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
