<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Declares Progress in Solving Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has announced that
the critical problems related to computer Y2K bug have been
resolved after making serious efforts over the past months.
</P>
<P>
To fulfil the task, the country has selected a dozen of key
sectors, according to the Tanzania National Committee for the Year
2000 Millenium Bug Problem.
</P>
<P>
Y2K Project Manager, A. B. Kowero, named the sectors as energy,
water, food, communication, transportation, finance, emergency,
health and environment, as well as law and order, defense, trade
and industries.
</P>
<P>
Of these, energy, communication, transportation and fiance are
being given priority, Daily Mail newspaper Thursday quoted the
manager as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said leaders of Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda met in the
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha some three months ago and agreed
to jointly resolve the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem means that computer systems may fail, with
potentially disastrous results, if internal clocks that record
only the last two digits of each year are unable to cope with the
change from 99 to 00.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure the nation that we have passed the dangerous mark
of the problem," Kowero said.
</P>
<P>
However, the official acknowledged that the country is still
short of funds to deal with the computer problem.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Tanzania needs 440,000 U.S. dollars to
solve the problem. Earlier, the World Bank donated 100,000 U.S.
dollars to the committee.
</P>
<P>
A task force set up by the government, with technological and
financial assistance from Britain, has started to work for the
aviation sector to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
The government has also urged the private sector to step up
efforts in charting out strategies to combat the looming millenium
bug problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
