<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Gardening Masterpiece Add to Expo Splendor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The novel design has made the
China Garden quite stand out at the '99 Kunming International
Horticultural Exposition due to open on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The garden is situated in the northwestern part of the main
site of the exposition, tilting from northwest to southeast, very
much similar to the topography of China. Prompted by this
similarity, the garden designer, Sun Ping, designed two green
belts to represent the Yellow River and the Yangtze River, the two
longest rivers in China known the "mother of the nation". The
green belt representing the Yellow River is 300 meters long and
the other one is more than 200 meters long, with 31 small gardens
representing 31 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions
distributed along the two belts according to their actual
geographical locations.
</P>
<P>
The design does not only exhibit the extensive and profound
gardening art but also facilitate visitors to view the gardens.
</P>
<P>
China's gardening art has a long history, featuring different
styles in different geographical locations.
</P>
<P>
The "Yu Garden", or garden of Henan Province in central China,
brings the visitor back to the culture of the Yin and Shang
dynasties (16th-11th century B.C.). The first thing to catch the
eye is a life-size bronze tripod with magnificent motifs and an
eight-meter high jade pole, an object used to pay sacrifices to
the heaven and earth.A section of arched stone wall are inscribed
on both sides with pictographic designs and writings that used to
be found on bones and turtle shells during the Yin and Shang
periods as well as family names that were originated in Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The "Qilu Garden", built by east China's Shandong province,
features Mount Tai, the Baotu Spring and Confucius for which the
province is reputed. All the ancient structures were built by
hand, with the surfaces treated with high-tech materials. Inside
the garden are also a bronze relief carving on which the exploits
of ancient Chinese sage Confucius and a tablet that represents the
treasure of China's calligraphic art.
</P>
<P>
The "Wanchun Garden" of Beijing presents the elegance and
magnificence of the imperial gardens while the Shanghai Garden,
named "Pearl Garden", displays the vitality of a modern metropolis.
</P>
<P>
The particular features of each province, municipality and
autonomous region in gardening art and garden structure are
represented in the China Garden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Efforts For Sustained Economic Growth: Economists(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Economists have called for improved financial services and
financial innovations to fuel the growth of small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs), the cornerstone of the light industry and
private sectors, as well as expansion of consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
China has already attached more importance to the financing of
SMEs in the first quarter as more SMEs-oriented credit departments
have been established in state banks and credit insurance systems
serving SMEs have been launched nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In a move to boost consumer demand, China has allowed
commercial banks access to consumer credit business, and new rules
governing the use of bankcards, credit cards in particular, which
will promote consumer credit remarkably, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Development of the capital market, including securities and
bonds business, will also help ease the burden of the state's
budget by diversifying financing sources, according to the
analysts.
</P>
<P>
China has set the growth of its fiscal budget in 1999 at 14.3
percent, five percentage points higher than that of the revenue.
In the first quarter, the state's revenue has grown by 26 percent
year on year to 232 billion yuan, while the budget has increased
by 17.5 percent to 184 billion yuan during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Economists predicted that there won't be much room left for
expansion of fiscal deficit and increased issuance of treasury
bonds, and called for a more active role by the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
A more open capital market and stronger connections between the
capital market and money market will help ensure steady growth,
they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
