<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving to Become International Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- China's leading industrial and
commercial city of Shanghai will step up efforts to reach the goal
of becoming an international financial center in about 20 years,
according to Vice-Mayor Chen Liangyu.
</P>
<P>
Overseas financial institutions and multinationals are
especially encouraged to participate in the effort, said Chen when
addressing the '99 China Business Summit co-sponsored by the China
Enterprise Confederation and the Geneva-based World Economic Forum,
that ended here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Over the next few years, Shanghai is going to follow
international norms in managing its financial institutions and try
to establish a financial supervision system that will combine
administrative, economic and legal methods.
</P>
<P>
The city will approve more commercial banks while bringing in
various types of overseas financial bodies, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Further measures will be taken to standardize the existing
capital, securities, foreign exchange and insurance markets. An
offshore financial market will also be set up together with that
for transactions of property rights.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has 62 overseas banking institutions and 162
representative offices of other such institutions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
