<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke042928 -ADB Expert Calls for Good Governance in Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- As the absence of quality
governance is one of the root causes of the banking crisis in
Asia, Asian countries should encourage good governance in the
banking sector, said an expert of the Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on "Financial Sector Restructuring in
Asia" here, Christine Wallich, director of the ADB Financial
Sector, suggested a number of tools for encouraging good
governance in banks.
</P>
<P>
"In certain countries, governments have established schemes to
assist banks to recapitalize either by injecting equity capital or
by purchasing bad loans. Any such assistance should be conditional
on corporate governance reforms in the affected banks."
</P>
<P>
Wallich said that institutional investors and multilateral
development banks should factor in the quality of corporate
governance in their decisions to do business with banks.
</P>
<P>
As providers of substantial capital, institutional investors
and other lenders can influence the quality corporate governance
in banks, he said.
</P>
<P>
The expert said that legal regimes must permit the take-over of
banks, bankruptcy or official intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The threat of losing capital or forfeiting control of their
banks should compel most owners to exert good internal
governance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wallich also urged rating agencies to throw the spotlight on
the quality of board governance in banks as one of the factors in
their overall evaluation of the integrity and soundness of banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0249 </DOCNO>
