<HEADLINE> Kenya Makes Second Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Two Kenyan cabinet ministers were
swapped together with two permanent secretaries and one new
permanent secretary was appointed in a cabinet reshuffle in this
east African country Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi made the cabinet reshuffle,
his second just within two months, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Previously minister Andrew Kiptoon of Cooperative Development
swapped places with Industrial Development Minister Chris Obure.
</P>
<P>
Nehemiah Ngeno was named as new permanent secretary in the
Ministry of Environmental Conservation, replacing Franklin Bett,
who was posted to Australia as High Commissioner (ambassador).
</P>
<P>
Ngeno, a long-serving chief economist, was until his new
appointment, the principal administrator in the Office of the
President.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary Barua Chele for Information and
Broadcasting was swapped with Simeon Lesrima, the Permanent
Secretary for Rural Development.
</P>
<P>
Just two months ago, President Moi made his first major
reshuffle in which Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae resigned after
he was relegated to the Ministry of Industrial Development.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Moi sacked Jimmy Angwenyi from his post as
Assistant Minister for Trade, and on Good Friday reappointed
Professor George Saitoti Vice-President, ending 14 months of
speculation over the the holder of the number two slot.  
</P>
