<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Considers Allowing Expatriate Ownership of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- As many officials urge the
government to allow 100 percent ownership of businesses by
expatriates, the United Arab Emirates (UAE) is considering
formulating a new law concerning this issue.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Economy and Commerce has no problem in
formulating a new law, as long as it is the right formula for a
flourishing business and plays an important role in attracting
investments," Thursday's Khaleej Times quoted a source of the
ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said many
officials from economic departments were calling for the full
ownership of businesses by expatriates so that they could get a
free hand in their economic activities, which could boost the
inflow of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The full ownership of businesses by expatriates, if
implemented, would remove the need for national sponsors in these
enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that any laws concerning this issue must be
approved by the cabinet after detailed deliberations.
</P>
<P>
"This is too serious a matter to be decided overnight, as it
touches the nerves of the national economy," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"I personally support the move and encourage it," said the
source, adding that it was necessary to give foreign investors
more freedom as the trend of economic globalization prevails.
</P>
<P>
"If we keep protecting the local businessmen, we shall
obviously be creating hurdles against the flow of foreign
investments," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said it would not take very long for new laws to be drawn
up, "which will be in favor of both local and expatriate
businessmen." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
