<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Continues Bombing Yugoslav Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 29 (Xinhua) -- NATO warplanes bombed Belgrade,
Podgorica and about 10 other Yugoslav cities early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In about four hours from 00:45 local time, powerful explosions
shook the capital, mixed with heavy anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
Industrial installations and residential areas in other
Yugoslav cities of Novi Sad, Pozarevac, Ruma, Pozega, Surdulica
and Krnjaca were also hit, reported the official Tanjug news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations continued in the southern Serbian town of
Surdulica. Until Wednesday afternoon, 20 bodies of civilians have
been found and more than 100 injured rescued from the wrecks.
</P>
<P>
General Dragoljub Ojdanic, Chief of General Staff of the
Yugoslav Army, announced Wednesday night on the Serbian television
that Yugoslav air defense forces had shot down 46 NATO fighter
jets, including an F-117A stealth bomber, eight unmanned
reconnaissance planes and 182 cruise missiles, since NATO started
airstrikes against the country on March 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
