<HEADLINE> Five Zambian Surveyors Released by DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The five Zambian surveyors
abducted by soldiers of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
have been released, Zambian local newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five were released Wednesday afternoon at Kasumbalesa
border post near Chililabombwe in the north of Zambia, where
Copperbelt Minister Matthew Mulanda received them.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers quoted Zambian Acting Minister of Information
and Broadcasting Services Bennie Mwiinga as saying the men were
all in good condition.
</P>
<P>
"I can confirm that the Zambians are in good physical condition
and are safe and back to their homes and families," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mwiinga thanked both Zambian and Congolese officials who worked
 tirelessly for the release of the five, adding that the relations
between the two neighboring countries had been excellent.
</P>
<P>
The five were on duty checking the border line west of
Kasumbalesa barrier last Saturday when the armed soldiers from DRC
pounced on them and dragged them into their side. The five
Zambians were accused of making reconnaissance for the rebels
fighting to topple DRC President Laurent Kabila. 
</P>
