<HEADLINE> Myanmar Lays Down Six-Year Plan for Drug Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has laid down a six-year
plan for perpetual elimination of narcotic drugs in Mongla region,
the eastern Shan state of the country bordering China, following
the declaration of the region as a drug-free zone in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the first three years of the plan, four tasks -- reclaiming
land in mountain and hill areas for terrace fields, making tests
to put the fields under high-yield paddy and other commercial
crops, ensuring sufficient water and power supply for hill
villages and building roads there -- will be carried out, leader
of the Mongla region U Sai Lin was quoted by Thursday's New Light
of Myanmar newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to lift people in the hill region out of
poverty and provide them with adequate food within the three
years, U Sai Lin said at a ceremony Tuesday marking the second
anniversary of the proclamation of the region as a drug-free zone.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there is dissatisfaction among residents in
the region who are in difficulties for livelihood due to lack of
effective material assistance.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that some residents asked to cultivate back poppy
and some already moved to the area where poppy can be planted.
</P>
<P>
"Though the cultivation of sugarcane, a poppy substitute crop,
has achieved success this year, things came to such a state that
the cultivation of sugarcane stopped as there was no way to seek
markets," he said, stressing that it is difficult for them to
maintain the success after eradication of poppy cultivation.
</P>
<P>
He requested the government and international organizations to
provide effective assistance to the region for the success for the
implementation of the six-year plan for perpetual elimination of
narcotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the people in the region will make concerted
efforts to raise the living standard.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has laid down a 15-year total drug eradication plan for
the whole country beginning 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
