<HEADLINE> Bangladesh May Fail to Fulfill Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh may not be able to
complete all the development activities under the country's Annual
Development Program (ADP) for the current 1998-99 fiscal year, the
Bangladesh Observer reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Only 44 percent of the ADP development activities were
completed during the first eight months of the fiscal year ending
June 1999, as against the target of 66.66 percent, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Planning Ministry said that only about 43
percent of the total fund allocated for the ADP for the fiscal
year had been spent, and now it was a great challenge to spend the
rest 57 percent to successfully implement the activities in the
remaining four months.
</P>
<P>
Under the ADP, 274 projects of a total 1,216 projects are to be
completed within the fiscal year, but only four projects have been
completed.
</P>
<P>
Another source from the ministry, however, termed the overall
activities satisfactory. "The development activities are not bad
at all even after the century's worst floods which the country
experienced last year," he said, adding that the rate of
development in the last eight months exceeded that of the same
period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The latest report of Implementation, Monitoring and Evaluation
Department under the Planning Ministry said that about 59.15
billion taka (1.22 billion U.S. dollars) were spent in the last
eight months, out of the total amount of 136 billion taka (2.80
billion dollars) in the ADP.
</P>
<P>
The rate of expenditure of the local currency increased, but
the use of project assistance fell, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
