<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Bigger Trade Surplus in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a bigger
trade surplus in March this year due to a higher growth in exports
compared with the same month last year, according to the
Statistics Department Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is the 17th consecutive month since November 1997 that
Malaysia continued to record a trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in March amounted to 6.5 billion ringgit
(1.71 billion U.S. dollars) against a smaller surplus of 4.0
billion ringgit (1.052 billion U.S. dollars) in the same month
last year, the department's preliminary "Monthly External Trade
Statistics" shows.
</P>
<P>
During March, the country's exports grew 5.9 percent to 25.7
billion ringgit (6.763 billion U.S. dollars) while its imports
declined 5.4 percent to 19.2 billion ringgit (5.052 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The department said the surplus in March was also higher by 1.6
billion ringgit (421.052 million U.S. dollars) compared with 4.9
billion ringgit (1.289 billion U.S. dollars) recorded in February.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of the year, the trade surplus was larger
at 15.7 billion ringgit (4.131 billion U.S. dollars) from a
surplus of 9.1 billion ringgit (2.394 billion U.S. dollars)
recorded a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, the bigger surplus in
January-March was due to a larger decline in imports of 10.7
percent to 53.7 billion ringgit (14.131 billion U.S. dollars) and
a marginal increase in exports of 0.3 percent to 69.4 billion
ringgit (18.263 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
