<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi University Closed Indefinitely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi university has been
closed sine die following violence on the campus unleashed by some
students on Sunday and Monday, local press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology (BUET)
was closed on Tuesday for an indefinite period, with all
examinations and academic and administrative activities suspended,
to avert further untoward incidents on the campus, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the university said a group of student,
numbering about 300, stormed the residential area of the teachers
and officials, the council building, several research sites,
provost offices of some residential halls, dining halls and common
rooms.
</P>
<P>
Computers, other office equipment and four cars were damaged by
the students and a teacher was injured, according to the press
release which also blamed police for "playing silent role during
the incident."
</P>
<P>
The students' action was triggered by the expulsion of a
student of the Civil Engineering Department, who was ousted for
impersonating another student in examinations around a month ago.
</P>
<P>
BUET Teachers' Association on Wednesday demanded steps to
strengthen security measures for teachers and stern action against
the students involved in the incidents, and a judicial probe into
the "mysterious and inactive" role of police during the incidents.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
