<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (59) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Why should the three issues be raised and solved during the
transition in Macao?
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth transition and transfer of government in
Macao, it is necessary to properly handle all major matters during
the transitional period, the most important ones of which are the
localization of the civil servants, the official language and the
laws.
</P>
<P>
The three issues are left over from history. When the two
Governments of China and Portugal signed the Joint Declaration on
the Question of Macao in 1987, conditions in Macao were
incompatible with its future return to China, which are shown in
the following three aspects:
</P>
<P>
1. The civil servants in Macao. The Portuguese Macao
Government employed about 10,000 civil servants at the time.
Among them, almost all the middle and senior level official posts
were occupied by Portuguese or their descendants (popularly known
as Macaense), while Chinese who accounted for about 97 percent of
the local population could only serve posts at the lower level.
This is obviously disproportionate to the population composition
in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, information released by the Macao Government shows
that the proportion of civil servants who were born in Portugal
rose sharply between 1980 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
2. Official language. Portuguese has long been the only
official language in Macao. All the laws promulgated by the
Portuguese Macao Government, all the communications between the
residents and the Government in Macao must be in Portuguese. A
test on Portuguese was compulsory for the recruitment or promotion
of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Chinese language which is the mother
tongue of the 97 percent of people in Macao was not used at all in
the executive, legislative and judicial activities in Macao. Yet
very few local Chinese speak Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
3. Local laws. The legal system in Macao at the time was
mainly composed of the laws in force in Portugal which were
extended to be applicable to Macao while the locally made laws
were few in number and insignificant. These Portuguese laws
enforced in Macao are outdated and out of step with the situation
in Macao.
</P>
<P>
What is more, they are written in Portuguese without being
translated into Chinese and thus not comprehensible to most local
Chinese residents. Furthermore, the judicial system in Macao was
affiliated with that of Portugal and all the judges and
prosecutors came from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly, this situation is absolutely incongruous with the
status that Macao will enjoy after its return to China. If this
situation was not to be changed, the Chinese Government would not
be able to smoothly resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao,
and it would be impossible to implement in Macao the policy of "
one country, two systems" as set forth in the Basic Law.
Therefore, it is essential for a smooth transition in Macao to
employ local people to public offices, make Chinese the official
language of Macao and localize the laws there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (60) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What are the specific tasks of the Preparatory Committee for
the Macao Special Administrative Region?
</P>
<P>
On April 29, 1998, the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress formally adopted, at its second meeting, the
Remarks by the National People's Congress on the Draft Name-list
of the Members of the Preparatory Committee for the Macao Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee is composed of 100 members, among
whom 60 are from all walks of life in Macao and 40 from the
mainland (including from the Macao Branch of the Xinhua News
Agency), with Vice Premier Qian Qichen as its Chairman and nine
Vice Chairmen.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee held its first meeting in Beijing
from May 5 to 6, 1998, during which Chairman Li Peng of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress issued an
instrument of appointment to each of the members and delivered a
speech. At this plenary meeting, the Detailed Working Rules of
the Preparatory Committee for the Macao Special Administrative
Region of the National People's Congress was adopted, a decision
was made to set up four working groups on the political, legal,
economic and social and cultural affairs, and the future work of
the Committee was discussed in some length.
</P>
<P>
As a working body of the National People's Congress, the
Preparatory Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region
has the following nine tasks:
</P>
<P>
1. Form the first Government of the Macao Special
Administrative Region, including working out the specific methods
for the formation of the Selection Committee for the First
Government and the selection of a candidate for the Chief
Executive, producing the Selection Committee and the candidate
according to the Methods, and deciding on the composition of the
First Government;
</P>
<P>
2. Work out specific methods for the formation of the First
Legislature;
</P>
<P>
3. Work out specific methods for the formation of the judicial
organs in the Macao Special Administrative Region;
</P>
<P>
4. Propose ways to handle the major legal matters related to a
smooth transition, including how to handle the previous laws in
force in Macao which contravene the Basic Law, and submit their
proposals to the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress for review;
</P>
<P>
5. Work out ways for the transition of the municipal
authorities;
</P>
<P>
6. Propose major measures and policies to be taken to ensure a
smooth transition in the economic, social, cultural fields and
order and stability in Macao;
</P>
<P>
7. Make a proposal on the implementation of the Law of the
People's Republic of China on Nationality in the Macao Special
Administrative Region and submit the proposal concerned to the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress for review;
</P>
<P>
8. Work out a detailed plan for the Celebration Ceremony for
the Establishment of the Macao Special Administrative Region and
related celebration activities; and
</P>
<P>
9. Handle all other important matters related to the
preparations for the establishment of the Macao Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Army Denies Killing Congolese Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan army has rejected
reports by the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) that its
soldiers killed six Congolese rebels and 11 Ugandans in Kisangani,
north of DRC, in a protest against their presence in the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
''This is false, it's a mere fabrication whose purpose is
obvious,'' Rwandan army spokesman Emanuel Ndahiro told Rwanda News
Agency, calling it a propaganda war by the Laurent Kabila regime.
</P>
<P>
Leon Kasonga, the DRC army spokesman, had said on state
television in Kinshasa that Rwandan troops opened fire on 400
disarmed Congolese rebels who had staged a protest march in Camp
Ketele, but did not say when the incident occurred.
</P>
<P>
''We are not aware of any incident of that kind,'' Ndahiro
said, adding the Rwandans are in good terms with the rebels they
are backing.
</P>
<P>
Jean Pierre Ondekane, commander of the rebel Congolese Rally
for Democracy, also refuted the report by the government official.
</P>
<P>
''Rwandan soldiers are with us since the beginning of the
rebellion, they are helping us and we fully collaborate,''
Ondekane told the news agency on a satellite phone from Bendera
town, in Katanga province.
</P>
<P>
However, well-informed sources in Kisangani gave another
version of the alleged protest. It is said that the protest
actually took place and was directed against the Ugandan People
Defense Force (UPDF) army chief of staff, Brigadier James Kazini,
who had arrested one RCD commander in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
''The Congolese rebels appealed for the release of their
commander and used the local radio to call upon residents to
protest against the UPDF senior commanders who have messed up
themselves with the Congolese,'' the same sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
