<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Meeting of Nations Bidding for EU Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The seventh meeting of the
parliamentary presidents of the countries bidding for European
Union (EU) membership concluded here Wednesday with the adoption
of two statements on the situation of southeast Europe and the EU
enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
All the parliamentary chiefs of 12 countries believe the
maximum open and transparent process is indispensable to the EU
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
European Parliament President Jose Maria Gil-Robles said at a
press conference that the EU will not classify the first and the
second groups of countries bidding for membership into different
classes but the entrance timetable for every country will be
different.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the EU speed up the reform work and better finish it
before the end of 2000, which will be also a prerequisite for the
success of the enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, opened on Tuesday, is attended by the
parliamentary leaders of all countries taking part in the EU
enlargement process, which are Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Romania, Slovakia and
Slovenia. The next meeting will be held in Slovenia. 
</P>
