<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Seeks Loans for Interoceanic Railway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua is seeking financial
support for an interoceanic railway project worth one billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The railway line, to be 473 kilometers long, will link the
country's Pacific and Atlantic coasts, from the Pacific port of
Corinto in the north to the Atlantic port of Monkey Point in the
south.
</P>
<P>
Last week a Nicaraguan mission went to Washington to seek a
credit for the construction of the railway, said the newspaper "La
Tribuna" on Wednesday, quoting Gilberto Cuadra from the company
SIT-Globa, which is in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The railway will extend almost half the length of the country
and be used for the transportation of containers from one coast to
the other, said Cuadra.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the railway line, the project will also include
the construction of 80 kilometers of highway and 168 bridges.
</P>
<P>
There have been signs that the Panama Canal can not meet the
increasing demands of world commercial activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
