<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank Pledge to Strengthen HIPC Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank pledged here Wednesday to strengthen the
Initiative of the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC).
</P>
<P>
At a one-day meeting in Washington, the Development Committee
of the two international financial institutions agreed to take
action to enable HIPC Initiative debt relief to be "broader,
deeper and faster".
</P>
<P>
A communique released after the meeting said the ministers "
expressed their continued strong support for the Initiative and
reaffirmed its overarching objective of poverty reduction".
</P>
<P>
The Development Committee, consisting of 24 members, generally
ministers of finance, advises and reports to the boards of
governors of the Bank and the IMF on the transfer of real
resources to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers reiterated the importance of ensuring a clear link
between debt relief and the goals of sustainable development and
poverty reduction and looked forward to the results of ongoing
consultations in this area," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also endorsed a set of principles that should be
used in considering changes to the current HIPC framework,
including ways and means to promote sustainable development and
poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative was launched in 1996 to deal with debt
problems of developing countries. So far, only two countries --
Uganda and Bolivia -- have received debt-relief assistance.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting on the lessons of the recent financial crisis, the
ministers also reiterated the importance of concerted action to
help countries to bolster their social policies and institutions.
</P>
<P>
They also emphasized the importance and urgency of work by the
World Bank and the IMF to help countries become better prepared
for crises, and to ensure that when a crisis strikes the most
vulnerable groups are protected and the process of longer term
development sustained.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided that its next meeting will be held on
September 25 this year in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
