<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees Early Recovery for Philippine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) expects the Philippine economy to recover this year, with
its gross domestic product (GDP) expanding by 2.2 percent due
mainly to a "fast turnaround" in the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
Business World Thursday quoted a recently released IMF report
as saying that a strong agriculture sector could very well make up
for the expected poor performance of the industrial sector in the
first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
GDP is the value of goods and services produced by the economy
domestically, and is one of the widest measures of economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The IMF report said some recovery in the industrial sector and
continued robust growth in the services sector will feed the
country's economy this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the continued strength of the export sector,
emanating from a strong demand for electronic products in the
international markets, will also give the economy the boost it
needs.
</P>
<P>
The IMF forecast, however, assumed the Philippine
administration successfully implements the economic policies it
has agreed to follow under a two-year standby program activated
last year.
</P>
<P>
The program puts emphasis on containing inflation at an average
of 8.5 percent for the entire year, reforms in fiscal management
and reforms in the taxation of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
With these reforms in place, the IMF said faster growth will
return in the medium term, at an average of 5 percent in the next
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
