<HEADLINE> Congress Denies Clinton Support for Bombing on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted late on Wednesday against a resolution in
support of NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was rejected on a 213-213 tie vote. Earlier, the
House voted 249 to 180 to limit President Bill Clinton's ability
to widen the Kosovo war, demanding the president to get
congressional approval before deploying ground troops.
</P>
<P>
The House's votes showed a great contrast to Clinton's appeal
for a "single voice" in Congress on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The debate was the first full House discussion about the Kosovo
crisis since NATO started bombing Yugoslavia on March 24..
</P>
<P>
The majority Republicans said Congress was merely exercising
its constitutional responsibility and forcing Clinton to keep his
word on not sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We should not even be in the Balkans," said Republican
representative Floyd Spence, chairman of the Armed Services
Committee. "The national security of this country is not at stake.
"
</P>
<P>
Doug Bereuter, representative from Nebraska, said: "Bombing for
peace is wrong and it's not working."
</P>
<P>
The Senate had voted bipartisan support for the airstrikes last
month. The House vote caught both Democratic and Republican
leaders by surprise. The administration said it would press ahead
with its airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
In response to the House vote, White House spokesman Jake
Siewert said NATO would continue its air campaign against
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
