<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Reports Growth in Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin scored some 2.7 billion U.
S. dollars in foreign trade from January to March, up 14 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In breakdown, exports made up 1.49 billion U.S. dollars, a rise
of 25.8 percent, and imports were 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, up 2.1
percent, according to sources from the Municipal Commission of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-two percent of this northern port city's exports, or 1.
07 billion U.S. dollars, were done by overseas-financed
enterprises in the city, up 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, both state-owned enterprises and private
businesses clinched bigger increases in exports according to their
respective export volumes in the first quarter of last year, said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the city's rising export momentum to local
efforts to promptly adjust foreign trade strategy and expand the
city's overseas-backed businesses.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin now boats over 4,000 operational overseas-financed
businesses, said the information.
</P>
<P>
China's imports surged 11.6 percent in the first three months
of 1999, the highest growth rate since the second quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The total import value amounting to 32.99 billion U.S. dollars
between January and March, and the overall trade volume for the
period was 70.26 billion U.S. dollars, up 0.3 percent, while
export value dropped 7.9 percent to 37.27 billion U.S. dollars,
said earlier reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
