<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Likely to Allow NATO to Use Its Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and NATO on Wednesday
exchanged notes on allowing NATO to use the country's airspace
within the framework of the "united forces" military action, the
Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exchanging of notes means the two sides have reached an
agreement on this matter, and the Bulgarian government will submit
a bill concerning the notes to the National Assembly (parliament)
for ratification, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules of the parliament, the voting will take at
least three days, said Iordan Sokolov, chairman of the parliament,
who was confident that the bill will be passed.
</P>
<P>
After NATO asked Bulgaria to give unlimited access to its
airspace to the alliance for military actions against Yugoslavia
on April 17, Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov went to Brussels,
the NATO's headquarters, to discuss with NATO leaders about the
details.
</P>
<P>
But as Bulgaria is not a NATO member, the military alliance has
to exchange notes with Bulgaria instead of signing a formal
agreement on the issue, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft, Bulgaria will open to NATO a 110-kilometer
wide air corridor to the east of the border with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, Bulgarian opposition parties such as the Socialist
Party has more than once expressed objection to the question,
saying that opening the country's sky to NATO goes against the
stand passed by the parliament of "not directly or indirectly
participating in military actions against Yugoslavia". They are
expected to vote against the bill, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
