<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wetland Reserve Established in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Northern Jiangsu Province, east
China, has set up a wetland reserve on the Hongze Lake, one of the
country's largest freshwater lakes.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, covering an area of approximately 1,670 hectares,
is intended mainly to protect the habitat of rare birds,
</P>
<P>
Hongze Lake is a lake where 143 species of migratory birds
live through the winter. Nine of the species, such as cranes and
swans, have been listed under the protection by an international
convention signed by China, Russia, Japan, the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), and the Republic of Korea (ROK).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the birds have been threatened by over-catching
of aquatic resources, imbalanced biological environment and
shrinkage of wetlands in recent years, and local experts have
called for immediate efforts for their protection.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is home to more than 40 species of water plants,
and some 50 kinds of fish, shrimp and crustaceans. Efforts will be
further enhanced to keep the habitat in the primitive state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
