<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Suffers Great Loss From NATO Strikes Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Croatia's tourism and air
transport industries lost about 10 million U.S. dollars in profits
during the first month of NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia,
according to Prime Minister Zlatko Matesahas.
</P>
<P>
He warned if the strikes continued in the travelling season,
Croatia's transport services would lose some 70 million dollars as
foreign ships and planes would not stop at Croatian ports or
airports.
</P>
<P>
NATO air strikes starting on March 24 have cost Yugoslavia's
neighbors 2.4 billion dollars in losses, particularly affecting
Croatia, according to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Croatian travel agencies were estimated to have lost more than
60 million dollars by May if the air strikes continued, and they
could only achieve 50% of planned incomes from tourism, said the
Association of Croatian Travel Agencies.
</P>
<P>
The travel agencies have appealed to the government for
financial aid and the Croatian government has asked for IMF loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
