<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Agrees to Deployment of More NATO Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov
has agreed that NATO increases its troops in Macedonia from the
present 13,000 to 16,000, said a spokesman for NATO forces in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Eric Mongot, said in the Macedonian capital of
Skopje on Wednesday that if need arises for this number to be
increased again, NATO will have to acquire another agreement with
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Germany will dispatch 1,500 soldiers each to
Macedonia for reinforcements, Mongot said.
</P>
<P>
Canada is also sending 800 soldiers to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
NATO will open an office in Skopje on Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO was reportedly planning a possible ground war in Kosovo to
drive out Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has been resisting NATO's efforts in persuading it to
allow NATO forces stationed in the country to launch ground
attacks on Yugoslavia from its soil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
