<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Exports Over 60,000 Tons of Fish, Prawn in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 29 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar exported a total of 62,400
tons of fish and prawn in 1998, 17,200 tons more than the previous
year, according to the latest Economic Indicators published by the
country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Fish accounted for 48,600 tons of the volume while prawn was
13,800 tons, fetching 58 million U.S. dollars and 100 million
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign exchange earnings stood at 158 million
dollars last year, a 23.4 percent rise over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, whose coastline extends as long as 2,276 kilometers,
is rich in fishery resources. Since the country adopted an
open-door economic policy in 1989, foreign investment injected
into the sector has reached 197 million dollars in 11 projects.
</P>
<P>
There were altogether 40,680 hectares of fish and prawn
breeding ponds in Myanmar with an output of 91,117 tons in
1997-98. Of the total output of 915,734 tons, 244,011 tons were
fresh water fish and prawn and 671,723 tons were deep sea fish and
prawn.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's per capital fish and prawn consumption was 17.97
kilograms in 1998, an increase of 330 grams over the previous
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
