<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Author Wins Lawsuit on Internet Story Infringement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A Beijing court yesterday ruled
in favor of a plaintiff whose story, published on his homepage,
was printed by a newspaper without permission, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was likely China's first case in copyright infringement on
works published on the Internet, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Chen Weihua, director of Beijing Rongyida Electronic Co Ltd,
posted a story concerning a computer program on a website (www.3d.
yeah.net) on May 10 last year, under the pseudonym "Wu Fang," the
name of the homepage owner.
</P>
<P>
Chen claimed that the article, which discussed the development
of MAYA, a 3-D animation making software, was accompanied by a
copyright statement saying: "All Rights Reserved; No Reprint
without Permission."
</P>
<P>
However, the Chengdu-based Computer Business Information Weekly,
upon receiving an e-mail from a reader recommending the story,
printed it in its October 16 issue, without permission from Chen,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The weekly refused to neither apologize to Chen nor pay more
than its standard fee for contributed articles, as demanded by
Chen, because it alleged that Chen could not prove that he was "Wu
Fang," the author.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Haidian District People's Court, after
investigating, confirmed that "Wu Fang" is Chen Weihua, because
Chen could log onto the homepage, change its password, upload or
erase files.
</P>
<P>
"The article should be protected by China's Copyright Law as a
literary creation since it was published on the Internet so the
public could read it," said Li Dongtao, chief justice of the court,
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
China just celebrated the fifth anniversary of its access to
the Internet last week, while the Copyright Law became effective
in 1991, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Targets Two Golds From Pool in SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Swimming
Association (PRSI) is optimistic the nation's swimmers will scoop
at least two golds in relay events in the 20th Southeast Asian (
SEA) Games in Brunei Darussalam in August.
</P>
<P>
PRSI's deputy to the technical committee Gerald Item said the
association would rely on eight key swimmers to maintain the
second medal position it gained in the 1997 SEA Games in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The swimmers would be selected from senior athletes, undergoing
training abroad and here, and junior swimmers who would be picked
from results of the three-day national age-group championship
starting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Only swimmers displaying the best form in various swimming
competitions this year will be named to the country's squad. They
are expected to meet Indonesia's best records produced in the 1997
biennial event.
</P>
<P>
"The association wants to send eight swimmers, at the minimum,
but we will also send several young swimmers who manage to attain
their best form to join their seniors in the SEA Games," Gerald
was quoted by The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In 1997, we only targeted four but we got 11 golds. This year,
we are targeting two to four golds from the men's and women's
relays because we faced a setback in our training program last
year due to the monetary crisis," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
