<DOCNO> XIE19990429.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Sees Emerging U.S. Information Appliance Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 28 (Xinhua) -- With the continuing decline
in PC prices and the overall softness in the PC market, a shift to
the information appliance market is underway in the United States,
according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The emerging market of home and office devices which can
transmit to or plug into common public or private networks will
completely shape computing in the 21st century, said the report by
4th Wave Inc., a U.S. market research and technology assessment
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
The market is not about the Internet, the report said, but it's
used as a platform for the delivery of products and services.
Winning products and services will help ease the burden of
individual lives through technology. This is not fundamentally
different from the role that technology played 100 years ago when
electricity, the automobile, the telephone and radio
communications emerged, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Driving the emergence of the market will be very cheap
computing power and pervasive connectivity of homes, workplaces,
automobiles and individuals. Home markets will drive the next era
of computing, and a significant part of the markets will be based
on services rather than products.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the report said, the service market in 2004 is
estimated at 8.3 billion U.S. dollars, compared with the product
market of 4.8 billion dollars. By 2005, services will represent 77
percent of the market. In total, the market will rise to 5 billion
dollars by 2001, 20 billion dollars in 2008, and reach 23 billion
dollars in 2009.
</P>
<P>
Based on an evaluation of the role of computing in the U.S. GDP,
an average selling price for information appliances will be 70
dollars or a service cost of 23 dollars per month.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the market transition is not just about
information appliances but the emergence of "the fifth era of
computing," a new era following mainframe, minicomputer,
workstations and PC.
</P>
<P>
"The fifth era of computing is going to be radically different
from the PC era," the report said. "This is essential as computing
become pervasive and the transition is made to the markets of the
21st century," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
