<HEADLINE>   Keegan Denies Contract Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- England soccer team manager Kevin
Keegan has denied reports that he has agreed to stay on as England
coach beyond this summer, according to local reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Keegan originally agreed to take charge of the England team for
four matches - last month's Euro 2000 qualifier with Poland, the
Budapest friendly game, and two more qualifiers next month against
Sweden and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
He then planned to concentrate solely on his job of chief
operating officer at Fulham after these games.
</P>
<P>
But a report in the Daily Mail newspaper, said Keegan had
already told Football Association officials that he was willing to
stay on as a part-time coach next season, before taking over on a
full-time basis in the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Keegan has rejected the claims, however, saying: "It is not
true, there has been no meeting at all."
</P>
<P>
And the FA's executive director, David Davies, speaking from
Budapest ahead of England's friendly with Hungary on Wednesday,
told the BBC no deal has yet been agreed.
</P>
<P>
FA technical director, Howard Wilkinson, has also refused to
say what he thought would happen after June.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing definite has been arranged," the former Leeds manager
told BBC Radio 4's Today program.
</P>
<P>
"It's a delicate situation at the moment. He's got
responsibilities towards Fulham."
</P>
<P>
But Wilkinson did drop a hint about the FA's preferences, and
when a decision would be announced.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly the FA have got to keep their options open in case, if
Kevin was their choice, he decided not to carry on.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the sooner it's sorted out towards the end of the
season the better."
</P>
<P>
According to the Daily Mail, Keegan's mind is already made up,
however
</P>
<P>
"It is not beyond the realms of possibility that I will be
staying," he is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I am in charge for four games of which we have already played
one and then we will wait and see."
</P>
<P>
Keegan is said to be delighted with the new set-up at the
Football Association in which Wilkinson is playing a key role.
</P>
<P>
"I have a lot of good people around me, including Howard
Wilkinson who has been invaluable to me and together we have got a
nice little team going.
</P>
<P>
"The FA is very professional, totally different from when I
played, and that makes it an easy job to be England manager - so
long as you keep winning." 
</P>
</TEXT>
