<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Remote Diagnosis Network for Military Hospitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 29 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide network of remote
medical diagnosis which has already linked up 150 military
hospitals has begun to take shape in China.
</P>
<P>
An official with the General Logistics Department of the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) said that by the end of next year
the network is expected have all military hospitals connected.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the network, which includes multi-media
computers, video cameras and fax machines and program controlled
telephones, can provide effective medical treatment for army
personnel stationed in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Currently more than 500 medical experts in dozens of
specialties from PLA hospitals are able to offer on screen
diagnosis for army personnel operating in areas with small
hospitals such as those in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, Inner Mongolia, the Tibet Autonomous Region and
the Xisha Islands.
</P>
<P>
The network, which is also connected to similar civilian
facilities covering over 20 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions, has already saved the lives of over 3,000
officers and soldiers since it was first introduced in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The network will also be important for the PLA when operating
in special conditions such as fighting flood control and during
wartime.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing Military Area Command, which took the lead in building
up the network in hospitals under its area military command, has
also been seeking ways it can be used in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
