<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Hammers the Scots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- British Sports Minister Tony Banks
has told a Scottish newspaper that the country's national football
team are under-achievers who are effectively "the West Ham of
world football".
</P>
<P>
The devoted Chelsea supporter repeated his call that Scotland
should merge with the other home nations and compete as a national
British team.
</P>
<P>
His comments came as Scotland prepared to test themselves in a
friendly against European champions Germany, and as the government
fights an election campaign for the Scottish parliament.
</P>
<P>
The poll for the new devolved body is just over a week away,
while the friendly match in Bremen takes place on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
"Scotland is one of the great football nations and have a
fabulous qualifying record," Mr Banks told the Scottish Sun.
</P>
<P>
"But they have never got past the first round and if you think
about them in English terms they are the West Ham of world
football- they never quite perform to their full potential.
</P>
<P>
"No-one can argue that Scottish football at its best is some of
the finest in the world.
</P>
<P>
"But Scotland never make it past the group stage and England
consistently fail to find that extra push in the final stages.
</P>
<P>
"As Britain they would win it," he predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Scottish Football Association rejected the call.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Banks is entitled to his opinion," said SFA president Jack
McGinn.
</P>
<P>
"However, there is no evidence to suggest that there is any
support in the home countries for a Great Britain team."
</P>
<P>
The minister admits that his beliefs are unlikely ever to
become a reality, although he is determined to secure a British
presence in the Olympic soccer competition.
</P>
<P>
That would require a Great Britain team to be formed, an idea
which has always been rejected by the four home Football
Associations.
</P>
<P>
They fear it could undermine their powerful status as separate
countries in Fifa.
</P>
<P>
"Fifa president Sepp Blatter is talking about the possibility
of a British team in the Olympics and I'd love to see that happen,
"said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"But if we want to enter a soccer team in the Olympics we must
find a way of getting round the fact we have four home countries.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe we could bring back the Home Nations Championship to
decide things as it used to be a big feature of the football
season," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
