<HEADLINE> Arsenal Calls for Yellow Card Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League football
club Arsenal vice-chairman David Dein is calling for a change in
the game's disciplinary system.
</P>
<P>
Dein, a possible candidate to become the next chairman of the
Football Association, wants the rule changed whereby players are
suspended after receiving five yellow cards, according to local
reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Highbury supremo thinks the current system is unfair to
both players and supporters and he does not want to see players
punished until they receive seven or eight bookings.
</P>
<P>
"The disciplinary procedures will be reviewed this summer with
managers having an input into the way these work," said Dein.
</P>
<P>
"I think they should be changed because at the moment teams and
fans are being denied the services of talented players.
</P>
<P>
"With the system of refereeing today there are a lot of cards
about. Maybe five cards for a suspension is too few and it should
be seven or eight. There is a double jeopardy because when a
player is sent off, a previous misdemeanor counts against him and
that is not right." 
</P>
</TEXT>
