<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scotland Stuns Germany in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Scotland gave the soccer world a
shock when it stunned Germany for the first time in 40 years on
Wednesday when 12 friendly internationals around Europe produced a
clutch of notable upsets.
</P>
<P>
Scotland, with a makeshift strikeforce following injuries and
withdrawals by several key players, stunned the reigning European
champions 1-0 in Bremen to continue Germany's recent run of poor
results.
</P>
<P>
There were also upset wins for Ireland over Sweden and Morocco
over the Netherlands in Arnhem.
</P>
<P>
In the glamour match of the night played in front of a 98,000
crowd, Barcelona drew 2-2 with Brazil in a Nou Camp game to mark
the Spanish club's centenary.
</P>
<P>
In other high-profile friendlies, Hungary drew 1-1 with England
in Budapest and Denmark drew 1-1 with South Africa in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
Germany made most of the early running against Scotland but
failed to turn their possession into clear chances.
</P>
<P>
The only goal came when Don Hutchison scored after 65 minutes,
his first goal for his country in only his second international to
send a 27,000 German crowd home stunned and angry.
</P>
<P>
Scotland boss Craig Brown, who said before the match that he
had so many problems finding a team he was worried about playing
the game, greeted the result with cautious optimism afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"We were fortunate but I would gladly swap that result for a
win in Prague," he said, looking ahead to his team's vital Euro
2000 qualifier against group nine leaders Czech Republic on June 9.
</P>
<P>
"It gives us a bit of optimism. If we play with the same spirit,
the same determination, then I think we can do something over
there," added Brown.
</P>
<P>
Ireland showed neighboring England the way to beat Sweden when
they defeated the runaway European Championship group five leaders
2-0 in Dublin with goals from substitute Graham Kavanagh after 75
minutes and Mark Kennedy two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Morocco were also surprise winners, beating Euro 2000 co-hosts
Netherlands -- although more than half the Dutch team were playing
for Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, narrowly eliminated after the first round in last
year's World Cup finals, took a 2-0 lead with goals from Youssef
Chippo (59) and Salaheddine Bassir (69).
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands' consolation came in the last minute through
Ruud van Nistelrooy.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, who will jointly stage next year's finals with the
Dutch, also lost, going down to a 1-0 defeat to Romania in
Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, who were jeered off after losing at home to Egypt and
Bulgaria last month, would not qualify for the finals on current
form after a string of four 1-0 defeats.
</P>
<P>
Substitute Ionel Ganea scored the winner for Romania just after
halftime, but the hosts wasted a series of scoring chances and
should have won more comfortably.
</P>
<P>
Ronaldo scored against his former club Barcelona to give Brazil
the lead after 29 minutes in a rain-lashed Nou Camp --with Luis
Enrique equalizing five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Rivaldo, of Barcelona then scored against his club for his
country to put Brazil back in front after 40 minutes with Philip
Cocu completing the scoring at 2-2 after 63 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In Budapest, an Alan Shearer penalty gave an unfamiliar-looking
England team the lead over Hungary after 22 minutes before Janos
Hrutka scored the equalizer with a 25-meter freekick after 79
minutes that flew past David Seaman in the England goal.
</P>
<P>
England coach Kevin Keegan gave debuts to five players and said
afterwards that he would like to take the job on a permanent basis
after his temporary tenure ends in the summer.
</P>
<P>
Only a great performance from Manchester United goalkeeper
Peter Schmeichel saved the Denmark from defeat in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
The Danes dominated the first half and scored through Ebbe Sand
after 40 minutes, but South Africa came back strongly after the
break and substitute John Moshoeu equalized after 72 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Poland scored a notable victory over the Czech Republic, who
like Sweden, boast a 100 per cent record in their European
qualifying group. Poland, chasing Sweden and England in their
qualifying section, beat the Czechs 2-1 in Warsaw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
