<HEADLINE>   Keegan Wants the England Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Kevin Keegan has confirmed he
wants to remain as England Coach - as long as he doesn't let
anybody down.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his experimental side were held 1-1 by Hungary
in the Nep Stadium on Wednesday, Keegan told Sky Sports talks are
ongoing but in essence, he does want to continue as England coach.
</P>
<P>
Keegan said: "I've had two chats with the FA and we are still
talking. But I don't want people to think that I don't want this
job because I do. It is a job I want, I just don't want to let
anybody down and that's what has made it difficult."
</P>
<P>
"The game against Hungary is another match under my belt at
this level, which gives me more experience, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Keegan took over the England helm from the sacked Glenn Hoddle
last February but said he would only be in charge for four matches,
ending after the Euro 2000 championship qualifier against Bulgaria
in June.
</P>
<P>
His currently shares his England duties with being chief
executive at recently-crowned second division champions Fulham.
His contract at the London club ends in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
David Davies, the acting chief executive of the English F.A.,
listened to Keegan's words and then told Sky that he was"very
optimistic tonight."
</P>
<P>
"People are obsessed by meetings and talks, which I can
understand, but the fact is Kevin and myself have regular
conversations. Kevin said after the last match that it wasn't the
right time to decide upon his future and that remains, " Davies
said.
</P>
<P>
Keegan had earlier denied a report saying he had reached a"
provisional agreement" to coach England full-time next year.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Mail's Wednesday edition had reported that Keegan had
met F.A. officials last week and told them he was willing to stay
on as a part-time coach next season and then take over on a full-
time basis in the summer of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
