<HEADLINE> North China Accelerates Export Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hulun Buir League in north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region has taken advantage of
its location at the junction of China, Russia, and the People's
Republic of Mongolia, by establishing an export base to develop
its economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the export volume for the league last year
increased rapidly to 298 million U.S. dollars, top in all the
region's cities and leagues.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the local government said that the league has
invested in the past three years over 300 million yuan (36 million
U.S. dollars) in the construction and improvement of its port,
raising its annual cargo transit capacity to 15 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of cargo transits said that 76 million yuan
have been used to expand the production of local specialties and
to upgrade the technology of their producers.
</P>
<P>
Now the export volume of agricultural, livestock, and wood
products, and small-sized machinery gone above 9.7 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the export base has also pushed forward the
development of other economic sectors, including the processing of
milk products, sugar cane, animal husbandry, and edible wild herbs.
The amount of the league's grain area, and total livestock, and
the fiscal income for the first quarter has been the largest
compared with corresponding periods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
