<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0840 GMT, April 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Clinton administration on Wednesday announced
a major revision in U.S. sanctions policy that will permit sales
of food and medical items to Iran, Libya and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The new policy calls for an exemption of such items from future
sanctions, but will not affect sanctions against Iraq, Cuba and
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told reporters that
the announcement was the result of a two-year review of overall U.
S. sanctions policy which concluded that allowing food and
medicine sales to above-mentioned countries "doesn't enhance a
nation's military capability or ability to support terrorism." (
US-Sanctions-Revision)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Heavy fighting erupted on the outskirts of Masiaka in
Sierra Leone, a senior officer of the west African peacekeeping
force ECOMOG said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We reached the gates of the town yesterday (Tuesday) and since
then the small arms battle and artillery exchanges for the town
have intensified," a report reaching here quoted the officer as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Masiaka is on the main road from the capital Freetown to the
interior parts of the west African country and the rebels holding
the town have blocked road traffic to the interior from the
capital. (SLeone-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The House of Representatives Wednesday voted to
limit President Bill Clinton's ability to widen the Kosovo war,
saying the president should get congressional approval before
injecting "ground elements" into the ever-expanding conflict with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The 249 to 180 vote blocked the funding of 6 billion dollars
that Clinton had earlier at a White House meeting with lawmakers
urged Congress to approve.
</P>
<P>
Majority-party Republicans said Congress was merely exercising
its constitutional responsibility and forcing Clinton to keep his
word on not sending ground troops to Kosovo. (US-Kosovo-Congress)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The European countries will not receive a large
number of Kosovo refugees from Macedonia, President of the West
European Union parliament Louis Maria de Puig said Tuesday in
Skopje, capital of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"The idea of transferring refugees from Macedonia to the West
European countries is not dominant at this moment. Therefore, I do
not think that there will be a massive transfer of refugees from
Macedonia to West Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Puig, who began a three-day visit to Macedonia Monday, said
that the West European countries want the Kosovo refugees to stay
in Yugoslavia's neighboring countries so that they could be
speedily returned to their homes in the future. (Albania-West-
Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will fly to Germany
Tuesday to meet U.S. pilots bombing Yugoslavia and troops aiding
hundreds of thousands of refugees from the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
"He'll be traveling to Spangdahlem... to visit with American
combat pilots and will also visit Ramstein... to see the base's
humanitarian relief operation," White House spokesman Nanda Chitre
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time for Clinton to see U.S. troops since
the U.S.-led NATO began bombing Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is due to leave Washington late Tuesday and to return
either late Wednesday or early Thursday, Chitre said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that another stop might be added to the
trip. (UN-Germany-Clinton)  
</P>
</TEXT>
