<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonian President Unhappy About NATO Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov
said Tuesday that he is unhappy with the way the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) treats his country.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian news agency MIA reported that at a press
conference held at the end of the recent NATO summit in
Washington, Gligorov expressed his dissatisfaction about the
Western military alliance's attitude toward Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
After his return to the Macedonian capital of Skopje from
Washington Tuesday, Gligorov told reporters that he does not
expect NATO to accept Macedonia as a member at present.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has expressed its desire for a NATO membership while
NATO, much against Macedonia's wish, just listed Macedonia as a
third-wave country to join it.
</P>
<P>
NATO, embarrassed with its failure to make Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to accept the conditions set by the West for
solving the Kosovo crisis after month-long air strikes, has been
reportedly planning a possible ground offensive in Kosovo to drive
out Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has been resisting NATO's efforts in persuading it to
allow NATO forces to launch a ground attack on Yugoslavia from its
soil.
</P>
<P>
Officially, there are around 12,000 NATO troops in Macedonia at
present. But NATO has been sending reinforcements and heavy
weaponry to Macedonia over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Although it was agreed that no more than 16,000 NATO troops
will be allowed to be stationed in Macedonia, there has been
speculation that the actual number of NATO troops in the country
has risen to 22,000, which have taken an offensive position.
</P>
</TEXT>
