<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes to Restrict Clinton From Widening Kosovo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives
Wednesday voted to limit President Bill Clinton's ability to widen
the Kosovo war, saying the president should get congressional
approval before injecting "ground elements" into the
ever-expanding conflict with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The 249 to 180 vote blocked the funding of 6 billion dollars
that Clinton had earlier at a White House meeting with lawmakers
urged Congress to approve.
</P>
<P>
Majority-party Republicans said Congress was merely exercising
its constitutional responsibility and forcing Clinton to keep his
word on not sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Let's not put our young men and women... in the position where
they are on the ground under fire and the president is consulting
with the Congress of the United States after the fact, of their
being in harm's way," declared House majority leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions set by the vote could even make it hard to use
the Apache attack helicopters that have been recently sent to
Albania, poised for attacking Serb ground forces.
</P>
<P>
"We should not even be in the Balkans," said Republican
representative Floyd Spence, chairman of the Armed Services
Committee. "The national security of this country is not at
stake."
</P>
<P>
In its first full debate since airstrikes began against
Yugoslavia on March 24, the House voted not only to restrict
Clinton's ability to commit ground forces, but also required the
president to first consult with Congress and get its approval
before sending combat troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The House debate was complicated by two other proposals by
California Republican Tom Campbell, which sought to force Congress
to make a stark choice between formally declaring war against
Yugoslavia or withdrawing U.S. forces from the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Both proposals are expected to be rejected, but must be voted
on by the full House under provisions triggered by the 1973 War
Power Act.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the White House meeting with lawmakers, Clinton
expressed reservation about measures like the one the House had
just passed, saying 19 NATO nations had expressed unity over the
weekend and "America must continue to speak with a single voice as
well."
</P>
<P>
Clinton pressed for quick approval of his 6 billion dollar
request to pay for the expanded bombing against Yugoslavia and
urged lawmakers to resist Republican-led efforts to double it. "We
must get a Kosovo funding measure passed and to my desk now," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
