<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Suppliers Launch New Body to Regulate Chinese Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The demand for effective
regulation of Chinese medicine and herbs in the UK has taken a
significant step forward Wednesday with the launch of a new
self-regulatory body by Britain's major Chinese medicine
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Medicine Association of Suppliers (CMAS), the first
of its kind across Europe, aims to oversee the supply of Chinese
medicine to practitioners and retailers in the UK.
</P>
<P>
"Traditional Chinese medicine and herbal remedies are
increasingly popular in the West, but they do need to be properly
regulated. The Association is committed to achieving this," said
CMAS chairman Henry Lee, who is also the head of Chinese Medicine
Developments at Britain's Middlesex University.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are 600 to 700 registered practitioners in
Traditional Chinese Medicine in the UK, treating more than 1
million patients each year. However, there remain some grey areas
under current regulation arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The CMAS, with 17 signed suppliers which account for 80 percent
of the total Chinese medicines and herbs imports in the UK, will
oversee the supply of herbs to up to 500 Chinese medicine
practitioners in the country.
</P>
<P>
One of the priorities of the CMAS is to ensure that the
majority of the UK's Chinese medicine suppliers are providing
"quality control" products, Robert Miller, managing director of
East West Herbs Ltd, one of the CMAS' members, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The CMAS will work to assure safety and quality of Chinese
medicine in the UK through initiatives such as authentication and
chemical assays of herbs, and the planned introduction of a
kitemark for the herbs.
</P>
<P>
Supplier members of the CMAS are also committed to a code of
practice under which they must ensure the supply of authenticated
herbs and genuine non-toxic herbal products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
