<HEADLINE> West Europe Not to Receive Large Number of Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The European countries will not
receive a large number of Kosovo refugees from Macedonia,
President of the West European Union parliament Louis Maria de
Puig said Tuesday in Skopje, capital of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"The idea of transferring refugees from Macedonia to the West
European countries is not dominant at this moment. Therefore, I do
not think that there will be a massive transfer of refugees from
Macedonia to West Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Puig, who began a three-day visit to Macedonia Monday, said
that the West European countries want the Kosovo refugees to stay
in Yugoslavia's neighboring countries so that they could be
speedily returned to their homes in the future.
</P>
<P>
Puig said that he will submit his report on the refugee
situation to German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, who holds
the current EU presidency, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He promised to make assistance proposals for the countries who
have taken Kosovo refugees in great numbers.
</P>
<P>
The West European countries should take mid-term and long-term
measures to help Macedonia cope with the grave situation caused by
the arrival of over 130,000 Kosovo refugees, he said.
</P>
<P>
He supported the idea of a Marshall's plan for Southeast
Europe, the Macedonian news agency MIA reported.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Macedonia, Puig met Macedonia's Urbanism
and Civil Engineering Minister Dusko Kadiesvski, Internal Affairs
Minister Pavle Trajanov and other Macedonian officials.
</P>
<P>
He also met with workers of the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees (UNCHR) and officers of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in Skopje.
</P>
<P>
Puig visited a refugee camp in Stenkovec, Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eight flights were scheduled to take Kosovo refugees
from Macedonia to Norway, France, Finland and the Netherlands
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
