<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises to Consult Congress if Ground Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
pledged to leaders of Congress Wednesday that he would seek their
support should he resort to the use of ground troops in the
Yugoslavia conflict.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the promise in a letter to the congressional
leaders, released after he met about 40 members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
The president said he was confident NATO air power would be
enough to force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to allow
ethnic Albanian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
However, if he changed his policy on ground troops, Clinton
said, "I can assure you that I would fully consult with the
Congress."
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, without regard to our differing constitutional views
on the use of force, I would ask for congressional support before
introducing U.S. ground troops into Kosovo into a non-permissive
environment," he said, meaning a hostile environment.
</P>
<P>
The Republican-controlled House of Representatives voted to
block funding for the deployment of U.S. ground troops in
Yugoslavia unless Clinton first gains the approval of Congress.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, the White House announced Clinton would go to
Germany next Tuesday for a brief trip to visit U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
He will meet U.S. pilots flying bombing sorties from
Spangdahlem Air Base and see humanitarian relief operations at
Ramstein Air Force Base. The U.S.-led NATO started bombing
Yugoslavia in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
