<HEADLINE> Ghana Calls for Peaceful Solution to Congo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) - Ghanaian Vice-President John
Atta Mills on Wednesday called for collective efforts to solve
the political crises in the Great Lakes region, particularly in
the Democratic Republic of Congo, to make way for the development
of the people.
</P>
<P>
 "It is our expectation that together we can work towards
restoring durable peace and normalcy to those countries in order
to create the requisite atmosphere for sustainable development and
progress of our peoples," the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
 Vice-President Mills made these remarks in meeting with
Zimbabwean High Commissioner-designate Ngoni Sengwe at the State
House in Accra, according Ghana News Agency report.
</P>
<P>
 Mills said Ghana recognizes Zimbabwe's efforts in searching
for peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
 On the situation in Zimbabwe, he said Ghana has followed with
keen interest the pragmatic measures taken by that government to
ensure sustained economic development and prosperity for the
people.
</P>
<P>
 He said particularly laudable is the setting up of the
National Economic Forum to tackle issues affecting its
development.
</P>
<P>
 Mills also commended Harare's "bold" implementation of the
Land Reform Program in a bid to eradicate poverty and achieve
social justice through land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
 On bilateral relations, the vice president recalled the bond
of friendship between Ghana and Zimbabwe, saying the two peoples
have been drawn together through their common fight against
colonialism and imperialism as well as their commitment to peace,
stability and progress on the continent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
