<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Continues Rising But Nasdaq Falls Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The enthusiasm for
manufacturing stocks on Wall Street kept the Dow Jones
industrial average in record territory Wednesday but the
technology heavy Nasdaq index continued falling on
profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed up 13.74 at 10,845.45 after pushing as much
as 103 points earlier in the trading. The blue chip stocks
moved into the record closing high of 10,831.71 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's second straight surge came as investors showed
their interest in low-priced manufacturing stocks. They were
encouraged by the Commerce Department report, saying that
orders for big-ticket durable goods rose 2 percent in
March compared with a 3.9 percent decline in February.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking pulled the Nasdaq composite lower in the
second consecutive day. The index was down 52.04 at 2,550.37
after falling 49.64 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 11.89 at 1,350.91 while
the NYSE composite index fell 2.95 at 640.32.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange index rose 3.62 at 777.69 but
the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.63 at 433.53.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-8 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,752 up, 1,281 down and 509
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 942.35 million shares from 888.22
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
